<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Trade Deficit With Germany Up in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Polish trade deficit with
Germany rose to 3 billion marks (about 2 billion U.S. dollars) in
1996 from 280 million marks in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between the two nations this year rocketed to
31 billion marks over last year's 25 billion marks, an increase of
six billion marks.
</P>
<P>
Polish exports to Germany dropped 2.5 percent in 1996 while its
imports from Germany surged 30 percent, according to the latest
statistics issued by the Polish commerce council in Cologne,
Germany.
</P>
<P>
The council attributed the deficit to economic depression in
Germany and the appreciation of the Polish currency zloty, leading
to a sharp reduction of Poland's traditional exports of lumber,
rolled steel products, coal, cement and food.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there is a greater demand for capital and consumer
goods in the Polish domestic market, which fueled the increase of
the country's imports of German commodities.
</P>
<P>
Germany now is the biggest trade partner of Poland. In the past
few years, half of the 70 percent of Polish exports to EU
countries have gone to Germany.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that an anticipated better German economy in
1997 will help Poland increase its exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
