<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-23 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, U.S. Open Talks Amid Hopes of Hebron Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Mideast peace coordinator
Dennis Ross met here today with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa as the Palestinians and Israelis were reportedly close to a
deal on Hebron troop pullback.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived early today on the last leg of his Mideast tour to
speed up the long-delayed Israeli troop redeployment from the last
West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to brief Moussa on the outcome of the talks to
overcome the obstacles hindering the implementation of the
Palestinian-Israeli peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Arriving late on Saturday, Ross went straight into meetings
with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in Jerusalem and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in Gaza City.
</P>
<P>
After the overnight meetings, the U.S. envoy said he hoped to
resuscitate talks faltering over Hebron and Jewish settlement. His
last mediation effort collapsed in October.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, calling the meeting "very constructive and fruitful" and
"important," said they discussed how to push the peace process
forward in all means.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's spokesman Nabil Abu Rhdainah said the U.S. envoy is
bringing several ideas aimed at closing a deal on Hebron.
</P>
<P>
The four main points are Israel's demand to pursue suspects in
Palestinian areas, reopening Mrtyrs Street in the heart of town
that was closed to Palestinians, arming Palestinian police as
provided in the original accord, and joint Israeli-PLO patrols.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Sunday, Israeli and Palestinian delegates negotiated
for six hours in a Jerusalem hotel.
</P>
<P>
The two sides accuse each other of foot-dragging in two months
of talks on the West Bank town, 80 percent of which was due to
have been handed over to the Palestinian Authority last March
under the 1995 Oslo II accord.
</P>
<P>
The date was missed following a wave of suicide bombing by
extremist militants in Israel in February and March. The accession
to power of Netanyahu's hardline government further complicated
the situation.
</P>
<P>
Israel calls for rewriting the redeployment deal to provide
better security for 500 Jews among 100,000 Arabs in the city,
while the Palestinians seek to link Hebron to further pullout
elsewhere in the West Bank under the Oslo autonomy accords.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton, who has won a second term, last
week criticized Israel's settlement expansion in occupied Arab
lands.
</P>
<P>
Despite all the diplomatic flurries, violence flared again when
three fire bombs landed near Jewish settler homes in the past two
days.
</P>
<P>
To top it all, media reports expect that a deal on Hebron is
to be signed later today or Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
CNN, monitored here today, also raised the possibility of an
Arafat-Netanyahu summit to finalize arrangements for the
much-awaited accord.
</P>
<P>
It quoted high-ranking U.S. and Israeli sources as having
raised expectations on the would-be signing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Radio also reported progress after a night of
intensive talks between Israeli and Palestinian representatives.
</P>
<P>
Both Arafat and Ross expressed cautious optimism following
the talks, but Ross admitted that difference remained between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
PNA Finance Minister Mohammed Nashashibi said that there has
been progress in all directions in the night-long negotiations,
said the radio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
