<HEADLINE> Italy Approves Budget But Challenges Lie Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 23 (Xinhua) -- With the Parliament's approval of
the 1997 budget, Italy still faces many challenges such as
economic reform and several other problems, local newspapers said
today.
</P>
<P>
While some media hailed the accomplishment of the government in
the past year, other major newspapers said the budget will lead to
"higher taxes, fewer hospital beds, more expensive petrol and
natural gas."
</P>
<P>
Italy's Freedom Front leader Silvio Berlusconi called for a new
political order that can facilitate reforms in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that all reforms require an agreement among political
parties on modernizing the country and putting the budget into
reality.
</P>
<P>
The Italian parliament on Sunday overwhelmingly approved the
government's 1997 austerity budget, bringing a sigh of relief to
Prime Minister Romano Prodi, who is enthusiastically pushing for
Italy's entry into the single European currency in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The budget is designed to reduce the deficit to 3.1 percent of
the gross domestic product (GDP) in 1997, approaching the 3
percent standard set by the Maastricht Treaty for the entry of the
European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU). The EMU plans to
launch the single European currency by the year 1999.
</P>
<P>
Italy, which successfully brought back its lira to the exchange
rate mechanism of the European Monetary System (EMS) in November,
is eager to be among the first countries to join the EMU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
