<HEADLINE> Russia, Iran Call for Immediate End of Afghan War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Iran issued a joint
communique here today, calling for an immediate end of the
fighting in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The communique was issued at the end of talks between
visiting Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeni Primakov and Iranian
Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati.
</P>
<P>
The two sides expressed grave concern over the continued
fighting in Afghanistan, the heavy loss of civilian lives and flow
of refugees.
</P>
<P>
They also condemned violation of human rights, prosecution of
individuals for political and ethnic reasons and obstacles
impeding U.N. operations in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that escalation of hostility would
threaten the integrity of Afghanistan and the stability of the
region.
</P>
<P>
The Russian and Iranian foreign ministers called on the
warring factions in Afghanistan to bring the fighting to an
immediate end and reach agreement on national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Iran emphasized the need for honoring the legal
rights of all parties and avoiding monopoly or superiority of one
over the others.
</P>
<P>
Primakov and Velayati called for an end to foreign
intervention in Afghan affairs as a prerequisite for settlement
of Afghan crisis.
</P>
<P>
They also said their countries will actively cooperate with the
United Nations, the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC)
and other countries concerned to help the warring factions reach
a settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
