<HEADLINE> Russian FM Opposes NATO's Eastward Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeni Primakov today voiced his strong opposition to eastward
expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Primakov said at a press conference that "the stance of the
Russian Federation has been negative toward the eastward
expansion of NATO."
</P>
<P>
"We don't care much for declarations. What is important is
our own interpretation based on which the expansion of NATO is
dangerous to Russia both geopolitically, politically and
militarily," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, he said, "the probable expansion of NATO can
give rise to a new division of Europe, which Russia absolutely
does not approve of."
</P>
<P>
On foreign military presence in the Persian Gulf, especially
the United States, he said, "definite measures should be
taken to resolve all crisis in the region."
</P>
<P>
"It is only then that the military presence of the foreign
powers in the region will be limited," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after his arrival in Tehran Sunday, the Russia foreign
 minister said that Russia will expand bilateral ties with Iran,
adding that the cooperation between the two countries is not
against any other countries.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure to Moscow today, he said, "Russia and
Iran are two neighboring countries and the Moscow-Tehran
relations are both in the interests of the two countries and the
regional peace and stability."
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed a memorandum of understanding here today
to control export of weapons of mass destruction and missile
technology.
</P>
<P>
They also signed a memorandum of understanding on visa and
consular affairs and issued two joint communiques on Afghanistan
and Tajikistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
