<HEADLINE> Nepali House Session on No-confidence Adjourned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The special session of
Nepal's lower house turned into a confrontation between MPs of
ruling and opposition sides Monday mid-night before it was
adjourned at 1:30 a.m. Tuesday (GMT 19:15 Monday) till afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The stalemate began late Monday when lawmakers from the two
sides were shouting slogans against each other.
</P>
<P>
Earlier opposition lawmakers had staged a sit-in protest in
front of the speaker's rostrum for about three hours to block the
speaker to call for the voting on a no-confidence motion against
Prime Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba and his three-party coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
They alleged that some MPs of the ruling side have kidnapped
one MP who was supposed to vote in favor of the no-confidence
motion tabled by main opposition the Communist Party of Nepal
(United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML).
</P>
<P>
Bhakta Bahaur Rokaya of the Nepal Workers' and Peasants' Party
(NWPP) was abducted early Monday by Home Minister K. B. Khadka and
two MPs of the main ruling Nepali Congress (NC) party for fears of
the approval of the no-confidence motion, opposition MPs said.
</P>
<P>
They maintained that only after the "kidnapped MP" is sent back
to the house the no-confidence motion could be put to vote.
</P>
<P>
The NWPP party, with three MPs in the house, announced Monday
morning that it will support the no-confidence motion against the
NC-led government.
</P>
<P>
However, Prime Minister Deuba denied at the house meeting that
his government had arrested any MPs of the lower house.
</P>
<P>
Monday's house meeting, starting at 11:30, earlier was
adjourned twice as opposition MPs opposed the voting and blocked
Prime Minister Deuba to reply on the no-confidence motion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
