<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crackdown on Poor Health Food Planned Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- A national crackdown on fake
and substandard health foods will begin early next year, reported
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Public Health, the action, which
runs from January to March, will start with an inspection of
manufacturers of health foods.
</P>
<P>
Publicity activities will also be organized to teach consumers
about nutrition and recommend high-quality products, said Su Zhi,
director of the Food Hygiene Inspection Division under the
Ministry of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers will be banned from marketing unregistered health
foods, and violators will be punished in line with the ministerial
regulation on the management of health foods that took effect in
June.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Public Health will provide guidance for those
who fail to meet State requirements, Su said.
</P>
<P>
Through the inspection, Su said, the ministry will gain a clear
understanding of the health food industry in the country and
gradually standardize production of health foods.
</P>
<P>
Su made the remarks yesterday in Beijing during a national
symposium on health foods jointly sponsored by the Ministry of
Health and Hong Kong Golden Sun investment Holdings Limited.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 experts and representatives from the health food
industry participated in the meeting to study the health food
situation in China and draw up plans for the future.
</P>
<P>
Su told the conference that there are approximately 3,000
enterprises producing health foods, and the Ministry has received
an increasing number of complaints about the quality of the
so-called health food products in the past several years.
</P>
<P>
Some products have never been inspected by the Ministry of
Public Health and some have been found to lack the nutrients
described in their advertisements.
</P>
<P>
In line with the ministerial regulation on health foods,
enterprises and foreign companies wishing to export such products
to China will have to report to the top health authorities and
receive inspections of their products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
