<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Health Workers Going to Countryside </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- According to a new regulation
from the Ministry of Public Health, urban health personnel will be
assigned to work in rural county or township medical institutes
from six months to one year, reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The rule, which goes into effect on January 1, will enable more
young, experienced health workers to help alleviate the shortage
of high-quality medical personnel in the vast rural areas,
improving medical services for farmers, said Chen Minzhang,
Minister of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
The new rule is one of several measures that the central
government will introduce over the next few years to speed
development of health care in the countryside, Chen said, adding
that the State will re-establish a pooled medical insurance system
in most of the vast rural areas by the year 2,000.
</P>
<P>
Rural medical workers will be placed in training programs to
improve health care services, Chen said. Cities near rural areas
will be asked to continue to support their surrounding rural areas
by training medical personnel, providing technical guidance and
donating necessary medical equipment for local medical units.
</P>
<P>
Ministry of Public Health investigations found that rural
inhabitants still suffer from shortages of medicine and physicians.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 90 percent of all farmers have to pay all of their own
medical costs. About half of the rural working poor are reduced
to poverty by disease, ministry investigators found.
</P>
<P>
The pooled medical system that was popular in rural areas in
the late 1960s was largely abandoned in the 1980s. Only about one
of every 10 rural residents has joined a co-operative medical
system.
</P>
<P>
Under such a system, participants pay premiums and some of the
medical costs; the collective pays the rest.
</P>
<P>
Five State organs have worked out a joint plan to develop a
rural co-operative medical system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Land Transformation Helps Jiangsu Yield More Grain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Jiangsu Province, in China's
eastern coast, plans to harvest an additional of 1.2 billion
kilograms of grain a year in the next five years by turning
356,600 ha of low-yield land into fertile fields.
</P>
<P>
The low-and-medium-yielding land is scattered in 205 townships
of 13 counties along the northern bank of the Huaihe River. The
region covers 656,000 ha of cultivated land, 70 percent of which
have low or medium output.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has invested 90 million yuan in land
transformation so far this year. The amount of government
allocation for this purpose will be increased to 120 million yuan
in each of the next four years.
</P>
<P>
As part of the effort to help poor people to lead a better
life, the move will increase the per capita income of farmers in
the region by 250 yuan each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
