<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Bronze and Stone Ware Found in River Valley in Guizhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 40 pieces of bronzeware
and four well-polished items of stoneware have been found among
silt near the Qingshui river in southwest China's Guizhou
Province.
</P>
<P>
The find was made by local people panning the ancient river bed
of Qingshui, according to the "China Archaeological News".
</P>
<P>
They found a bronze sword, axe, arrow head and fishing hook
from the Warring States period (475-221 BC), stone axe and a
sickle from the Late Stone Age, and pottery, porcelain and silver
ingots from the Song (960-1279), Ming (1368-1644) and Qing
(1644-1911) dynasties.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the find will contribute greatly to the study
of local ancient culture, Yelang, and the relationship between Chu
Culture in central China and Yelang Culture in the southwestern
part of the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
