<HEADLINE> Talent Fair to Help College Graduates Find Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Although the job market in
Beijing is not at its best, college graduates will be given an
opportunity to meet potential employers at a "talent fair" to be
held here in January, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Li Chaogang, a senior official from the city's
personnel administration, as saying that an unprecedented 59,000
graduates in the capital were expected to be seeking jobs in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The figure is 4,000 more than in 1996, said Li.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that the job market should have openings
for about 57,000 graduates, thus the demand for and supply of
talent will be closely balanced this year, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The positions will require more talented individuals with
higher degrees. More than 7,000 college graduates with only two or
three years of college education, will have to compete for the
2,500 positions available to them, according to Han Qinglin,
another senior official from the city's personnel administration.
</P>
<P>
The fact that many graduates are exercising greater selectivity
in the job market has contributed to the more stringent demands of
the job market and of the higher expectations from college
graduates, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
As a result, employers frequently complain that they find it
hard to fill positions they have vacancies for, while job-seekers
often can not find suitable jobs.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 units, including Government departments,
state-owned and non state-owned enterprises, joint-ventures and
foreign firms in Beijing will enroll employees at the fair, which
is expected to attract 10,000 job-seekers.
</P>
<P>
Units from other provinces will also take part in the fair, Li
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
