<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Measures For Improving Shanghai's Living Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Additions to existing houses
should go hand in hand with the rebuilding of apartments to
improve living conditions for Shanghai's residents, according to
an article in the latest issue of China's "Real Estate News".
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, China's largest city had a combined
residential floor space of 119.06 million sq m, but only 50.7
percent of that had proper facilities, and 58.7 million sq m
lacked necessities, such as kitchens or toilets.
</P>
<P>
The article noted that it would take 24 years to remove those
houses and to build standard flats at the current annual
construction rate of two to three million sq m of flats.
</P>
<P>
In an interview, Zhong Yongjun, chief engineer with the
Shanghai Administration of Real Estate, said that additional
facilities are a must, and that 10 million sq m must be added
annually to meet the goal of giving 70 percent of Shanghai's
houses the necessary basic facilities by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
He said that close cooperation between departments,
preferential local government policies, various kinds of fund
raising, and the active participation of residents are
prerequisites for the success of the improvement campaign.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 1995, a combined floor space of 35 million sq m of
flats was built in Shanghai, and dangerous or old housing with a
total floor space of 11.6 million sq m were demolished.
</P>
<P>
During that period, the city added facilities to 400,000 sq m
of substandard housing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
