<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wildlife Protection In China's Largest Nature Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, December 24 (Xinhua)-- The Antelopes of Hoh Xil, in
China's Qinghai Province, used to react in panic at the sound of
shots, but now graze and drink water in a carefree manner in the
largest uninhabited part of northwest China.
</P>
<P>
In 1984, illegal hunters slipped into the uninhabited zone, and
caught or killed rare animals, with more than 30,000 peasants
joining the activity, creating havoc.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands wild yaks, wild ass, antelopes, snow
leopards, and other rare animals were killed in the 90,000-sq-km
of the zone, which stretches across Qinghai, and the Tibet and
Xinjiang regions. The ecology and environment were devastated in
the process.
</P>
<P>
After that, a campaign was launched to rescue the zone, and
from October of last year to May this year, 12 groups of poachers,
involving 83 people, were caught, along with 1,000 antelope hides,
19 firearms, and more than 30,000 cartridges.
</P>
<P>
On January 18, 1994, Gyaisam Soinam Targyai, deputy party
secretary of Zhiduo county in Qinghai province, was shot dead
while trying to stop the killing of rare animals.
</P>
<P>
The crime shocked the people nationwide, and increasing numbers
of people, especially policemen and ex-servicemen, began to devote
their energies to the protection movement, and militiamen have
been sent to the zone seven times to crack down on illegal
activities over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The area was declared a nature reserve in 1995 by the Qinghai
provincial government, and seven members were added to the zone's
administration committee, along with 69 staff members.
</P>
<P>
An eight-man police patrol and ten ex-servicemen are now
responsible for making rounds 24 hours a day, and the wild animals
and mineral resources in the reserve at last have some more
effective protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
