<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Relics Found In 800-year-old Chinese Pagoda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 10,000 rare relics
have been found in an underground palace and a hidden chamber of a
pagoda in Shanghai's Jiading District.
</P>
<P>
The relics include Buddhist scripts, jade, coins, and gold and
silver sculptures from the Song (960-1279), Yuan (1271-1368), and
Ming (1368-1644) dynasties. The items were discovered during work
on the endangered pagoda.
</P>
<P>
The pagoda was started in 1205, and is one of Shanghai's
oldest. It was quite weather-beaten by the time repair work
started in 1995.
</P>
<P>
While technicians were digging a well to the northwest of the
pagoda, they discovered the underground palace and a great number
of relics. Further research led to more relics in a hidden chamber
at the top of the pagoda.
</P>
<P>
In response to the find, the district government put documents
on present local social development and models of high-tech
products into the underground palace and the top chamber. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
