<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gaps Among Regions in Brazil Narrowed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The once wide economic
gaps among Brazil's different regions have been narrowed over the
past few years, according to the Institute of Applied Economic
Research (IIEA) today.
</P>
<P>
The institute said that in 1994, the real products of the
relatively poor northern and northeastern regions grew 7.7 and 6.6
percent respectively, higher than those of the rich southern and
southeastern zones of 5.6 and 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
And in 1995, although Brazil's economic indicator fell, the
northern region still enjoyed an unprecedented growth of 8.7
percent, while the northeast gained 4.5 percent, 0.3 percent over
the national average.
</P>
<P>
IIEA partially attributed the narrowing to the combination of
the inflation drop and thriving trade.
</P>
<P>
But the southeastern zone still brings out 57 percent of
Brazil's gross domestic production (GDP), the IIEA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
