<HEADLINE> Shandong to Export More Machinery by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province
has set a target to export four billion US dollars worth of
machinery a year by the turn of the century, "China's Machinery
and Electronics News" reported.
</P>
<P>
The province intends to resort to exports to gear up
development of the local machine-building Industry, which won
nearly 1.4 billion US dollars in foreign exchange from exports in
1995, a big leap from 320 million US dollars in 1990.
</P>
<P>
This means that during the 1990-1995 period, the annual growth
rate of the local sector's foreign exchange from exports reached
34 percent, higher than the 30 percent national average.
</P>
<P>
In order to improve exports, the industry will give priority to
ten leading, technology-intensive and high-value-added products,
including numerically-controlled machine tools, forging equipment,
engineering machinery, tractors, diesel engines, freezing
equipment, ships, electrically-driven machines and vehicles for
farm use.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the industry will also increase exports of some
other products, such as grinding apparatus and abrasive, machine
tool parts, valves, cables, instruments and meters, bearings,
hardwares and fasteners.
</P>
<P>
By the turn of the century, the sector aims to build 55 key
export-oriented enterprises, including five with annual foreign
exchange income from exports surpassing 30 million US dollars, 10
with more than 10 million US dollars, and 10 with more than five
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the industry also plans to attract overseas investment
for processing projects and high-value-added items to speed up its
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
