<HEADLINE> U.N. to Appoint Special Envoy for Great Lakes Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Members of the
U.N. Security Council today agreed with Secretary-General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali's report calling for the appointment of another
special envoy for the Great Lakes region in Africa instead of
deployment of a multi-national force.
</P>
<P>
Council President Paolo Fulci of Italy said that in light of
the new situation in the region, the Council members agreed that
the functions of the multi-national force will come to an end.
</P>
<P>
"The general feeling is that in the next few months, the
Council should take a more comprehensive and more integrated
approach to the issue."
</P>
<P>
He noted that suggestions of more involvement were made
following the debate of non-governmental organizations and other
humanitarian organizations.
</P>
<P>
"The members of the Council shared the view that genocide
cannot remain unpunished and expressed their strong support for
the International Tribunal for Rwanda," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council decided to establish a multi-national
force for humanitarian purpose on November 15 when the situation
in the Great Lakes region, especially eastern Zaire, was
deteriorating with more than one million refugees starving.
</P>
<P>
Then in the following weeks, with the majority of refugees in
eastern Zaire returning to Rwanda, it became no longer necessary
to deploy the multi-national force there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
