<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Residents Enjoy Longer and Healthier Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Beijing residents are now
enjoying a far more healthier life compared with several decades
ago, according to a report from the local health bureau.
</P>
<P>
The average life expectancy of the capital city's residents
reached 74 years last year, more than 30 years longer than that
before the foundation of new China in 1949, the report said.
</P>
<P>
An official at the bureau attributed the prolonged life
expectancy to fine economic growth, social progress and the
improved health care system in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
He said that the major health index of the city have already
reached or got close to that of the moderately-developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of epidemic diseases has dropped dramatically in
the past dozen years. Compared with the figures of 1985, the
incidence of hepatitis has dropped by 67 percent to 55 per 100,000
in 1995, the incidence of dysentery, by 78 percent to 232 per
100,000, scarlet fever, by 90 percent to 7 per 100,000 and the
measles, by 96 percent to 37 per 10 million.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the efforts of the medical workers, smallpox, which
had been rampant in the city before 1949, was almost eliminated
and no cases of wild polio have been discovered in the past 11
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Takes Legal Action to Protect Wild Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- China will extend legal
protection to selected wild plants as it has for endangered wild
animals, reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Wild Plants Protection Regulations, ratified by the State
Council on September 30, will take effect on January 1, said Chen
Jianwei, deputy director of the Wild Animal and Forestry
Conservation Department, under the Ministry of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
The protected plants will be divided into two major categories,
Class One and Class Two, covering sub-divisions such as endangered
plants, and culturally and economically valuable plants. The list
will then be ratified by the State council, said Chen.
</P>
<P>
China is home to more than 30,000 kinds of plants, 12 percent
of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
The ministries of forestry and agriculture will enforce the new
protective regulations, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, precious plants, especially those with market
value, have been threatened by over-cutting, Chen explained.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations, together with the Wild Animal Protection
Regulations issued in 1988, are expected to help curb illegal
damage and trading of precious flora and fauna.
</P>
<P>
Violators of the plant preservation regulations will be fined
10 times the market value of the protected flora.
</P>
<P>
Criminal laws, reportedly, will impose still heavier
punishments for illegal activities involving protected flora and
fauna.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that in the past, because of light penalties, illegal
activities were rampant in some areas.
</P>
<P>
Chen also attributed the still-pervasive damage done to animal
and plant species to irresponsible local officials. He noted that
their awareness of their responsibilities towards protected plants
and animals should be raised.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen, the Ministry of Forestry regards flora and
fauna as a single, whole system to be preserved.
</P>
<P>
China has established 574 reserves for wild animals and
plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Liquidate Ailing Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia (BI), the
central bank, has set liquidation as the last option if certain
steps fail to save a bank facing financial trouble, a BI official
said.
</P>
<P>
Hendrobudyanto, director for banks development, told local
press Monday that the government has decided a legal basis to
liquidate an ailing bank if a number of steps like fresh capital
injection, merger and transfer of management, fail to recover its
financial trouble, newspapers here reported today.
</P>
<P>
The new regulation, which aimed to complement the central
bank's efforts to cope with problem banks, provides better
protection for depositors, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said whenever a bank was liquidated, depositors must be paid
after an appointed liquidation team pays all salaries owed, court
fees, auction fees, taxes and administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
Before this regulation, a bank's depositors were considered a
company's non-preferred creditors.
</P>
<P>
The director said the regulation was timely. The previous rules
had often complicated bank liquidation.
</P>
<P>
Banking analysts often cite Bank Summa and Bank Umum Majapahit
which failed in 1992 as examples of this complexity. Their
liquidation is still proceeding.
</P>
<P>
Bank Summa was closed in 1992 because of bad loans worth around
500 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Before the new regulation, bank liquidation was based on the
1995 Companies Law, which stipulates that companies including
banks can be dissolved three ways: by resolution of the company's
shareholders, expiry of the company's operational life or by a
court decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
