<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Govt Dispatches Seeds To North Part </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 24 (Xinhua)-- The Sri Lankan government has
dispatched over 2,900 tons of paddy seed to the Jaffna Peninsula
over the past two months, according to official sources today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that more than 34,400 farming families in the
recaptured areas are now busy with their work and they have
prepared over 7,500 hectares to cultivate paddy in the coming
season.
</P>
<P>
The government has made arrangements to despatch another 1,500
tons of paddy seed to the peninsula as the target of 6,000
hectares set by the government earlier was surpassed.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government has also made arrangements to
provide the farmers with 1,700 tons of fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that 150 tons of seed potatoes, onion and
vegetable seeds will also be distributed among the farmers in the
areas.
</P>
<P>
Jaffna Peninsula was once the stronghold of the Tamil rebels
who have been waging a 13-year war for a separate state in the
north-east of the island country. The peninsula was recaptured by
the government troops last May.
</P>
<P>
All farming land on the peninsula had been abandoned for over a
decade as a result of the rebel activities in the areas, the
sources said. Since the recapture of these areas, the government
has been helping the farmers resume their day-to-day activities,
they added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
