<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Retailers Enjoy Brisk Sales During Christmas Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Retailers across the U.S.
have been enjoying better-than-expected sales as shoppers stepped
up their spending on the final weekend before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
Many merchants have been expecting sales increases to be up 4
percent to 9 percent this holiday season over last year, according
to a report of the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
The traditional holiday shopping season between Thanksgiving
and Christmas was five days shorter than last year, but spending
was up, particularly for jewelry, apparel and toys. A few of the
big chain stores reported double-digit sales increases.
</P>
<P>
Price cut is the universal tool used by retailers, some of whom
cut the prices of their goods up to 75 percent. Consumers thronged
to the well decorated stores and malls to make their last minute
rush to fill up their shopping lists.
</P>
<P>
The computer market saw a sales pick up during the holiday
shopping season, as more people took the benefit of price-cutting
by some big companies. At Circuit City, a major electronic gadget
seller, large-screen televisions are also selling well. Another
hot item is a new crop of hand-held computing devices.
</P>
<P>
Devices for connecting a television set to the Internet using a
service known as WebTV Networks have attracted a lot of interest,
but the attention has not yet translated into big sales.
</P>
<P>
According to analysts, consumers at this time last year
bought up home PC's based on Intel's Pentium processors in order
to run Windows 95, the new Microsoft operating system released then.
</P>
<P>
This year, the only thing driving purchases are prices that can
push unit sales up easily.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Commerce Department said today that consumer spending
was up 0.5 percent in November. While that was down from a 0.7
percent gain in October, it was still slightly better than the 0.4
percent rise many analysts had been expecting.
</P>
<P>
An overall rise has been widely expected for the Christmas
sales, compared with that of last year, which was described by
many retailers as "terrible." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
