<HEADLINE> US Government to Delay Inflation-Bond Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government is
delaying the auction for its new inflation-adjusted bonds, an
official of the U.S. Treasury Department said today.
</P>
<P>
Roger Anderson, deputy assistant treasury secretary for federal
finance, said that final terms and conditions, which market
participants will also need to review, had not been finalized for
the new securities.
</P>
<P>
"It is extremely unlikely that we will have an early January
auction date. We are looking at a slight delay," Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the size of the offering was uncertain.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
announced the establishment of the new investment instruments last
May.
</P>
<P>
The new 10-year securities will offer protection against
inflation and pay a guaranteed real rate of return as the
inflation is eating into investors' returns.
</P>
<P>
The auction of the new bond had been set for January 15 and no
new date for the sale has been picked. 
</P>
