<HEADLINE> International Drug Sales Up 7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Pharmaceuticals sales in the
world's 10 markets rose 7 percent in the first 10 months of this
year, according to IMS International, the specialist drugs
industry market researchers.
</P>
<P>
The increase makes it increasingly likely that 1996 will have
been one of the best years of the decade for the drugs industry.
</P>
<P>
The United States was the biggest market with sales of 48
billion U.S. dollars, a rise of 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Germany, the third biggest market, also grew by 8 percent to 14
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
But growth was held back by Japan, where sales came to 19.2
billion dollars, a rise of 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
By medical area, nervous system drugs grew quickly, with sales
up 13 percent to 16.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sales of heart disease drugs amounted to 20.5 billion dollars,
an increase of only 3 percent. Heart drugs could soon be overtaken
by digestive system drugs, where sales went up 8 percent to 20.1
billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
