<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Extends Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council today decided to extend the mandate of the United
Nations Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP) for a further
period ending June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted unanimously, the council deplored the
violent incidents of August 11 and 14, September 8 and October 15,
which resulted in deaths of three Greek Cypriot civilians and one
member of the Turkish Cypriot Security Forces, as well as injuries
to civilians and UNFICYP personnel.
</P>
<P>
While emphasizing the need to maintain law and order, the
Security Council demanded that both parties prevent unauthorized
incursions into the buffer zone, and respond immediately and
responsibly to any demonstrations which violate the buffer zone
and any demonstrations near the buffer zone that might lead to an
increase in tensions.
</P>
<P>
The council called on the parties to accept the following
reciprocal measures:
</P>
<P>
-- to extend the 1989 unmanning agreement to other areas where
the two sides remain in close proximity to each other;
</P>
<P>
-- to prohibit loaded weapons along the cease-fire lines; and
</P>
<P>
-- to adopt a code of conduct, based on the concept of minimal
force and proportional response, to be followed by troops on both
sides along the cease-fire lines.
</P>
<P>
The council also called on the military authorities on both
sides to clear all minefields and booby-trapped areas, to cease
military construction near the buffer zone, and to refrain from
any military exercises along the buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
After the outbreak of violence between Greek Cypriot and
Turkish Cypriot communities in December 1963, the Security Council
decided to establish a peacekeeping force there on March 14, 1964.
</P>
<P>
The mandate of the peacekeeping force includes using its best
efforts to prevent a recurrence of fighting, contributing to
maintenance and restoration of law and order and a return to
normal conditions.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the council has periodically extended the mandate
of the peacekeeping force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
