<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- France and Russia will launch
their sixth joint space flight in the second quarter of 1997, in
which French astronaut Leopold Eyharts will stay 21 days at the
Russian space orbiter Mir.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Post, Telecommunications and Space said today
that the seventh Franco-Russian space flight will be launched in
1999, with a long duration flight of astronauts in space to
prepare for the staging of the international space station Alpha.
</P>
<P>
The two definitive agreements were signed today in Moscow
between the French space group the Centre National d'Etudes
Spatiales, the Russian Space Agency and the Energia consortium.
</P>
<P>
The first French spacewoman, Claudie Andre-Deshays, stayed 14
days on board the Mir in August this year, in which she did a
series of biological and medical experiments. 
