<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-23 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from Middle East countries;
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's Ministry of Agriculture has announced that
imports of vegetables now require an import permit, which is
granted by the ministry, Beirut's Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The new stipulation applies to squash, eggplant, cucumbers
and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
This move is aimed at controlling imports to support local
produce and keep prices down, the report said.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri has denied
that Lebanon will pay a "political price" in exchange for the
grants and low-interest loans promised in the Friends of Lebanon
Conference last week.
</P>
<P>
Hariri was quoted by Beirut's As-Safir daily today as saying
that the achievements made by his government in the past four
years was the card he used in the conference held in Washington
on December 16.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister described the conference, which was
attended by 29 countries and eight international financial
institutions, as "successful and positive."
</P>
<P>
In the Washington gathering, donor countries expressed
readiness to provide 3.2 billion dollars between 1997 and
2000, with one billion available for the next year. Lebanon
had hoped to raise 5 billion dollars for the implementation
of a five-year plan.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran will raise oil production from 3.6 million
barrels per day this year to 4 million barrels per day
next year, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Persian daily Akbar reported that the plan was made by the
Iranian cabinet headed by President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani and
was debated in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Iran, the fourth largest oil producer and the second largest
oil exporter in the world, pumps out 3.6 million barrels per day
and exports 2.5 million barrels per day in accordance with the
quota set by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC).
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Nateq-Nouri, head of the oil affairs commission of
the Parliament, said that the Iranian government would like to
sell its crude oil at 16.5 to 17 U.S. dollars per barrel
next year.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iranian oil is presently selling in
international markets at a price of 18.8 U.S. dollars per
barrel.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Tariff exemptions for imports are no longer allowed
in Sudan, according to an amendment made to the income tax law and
the customs law.
</P>
<P>
Under a decree issued by Sudanese President Omar Bashir Sunday,
a tax is levied on profits resulting from any commercial
transactions, regardless of other rules allowing tax or tariff
exemptions.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers today quote Finance Minister Abdul Wahab Osman
as saying that this amendment is aimed at raising the ratio of trade
and economic activities in the national income, increasing
revenues and eradicating deformities in economy. 
