<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Personal Incomes, Spending Up in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Personal incomes in the
U.S. increased in November while consumer spending also went up,
the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that personal incomes rose by 0.5 percent
in the month after being flat in October.
</P>
<P>
The number of people employed, the average number of hours
worked and the average hourly earnings all showed increases. Wages
and salaries, the key part of incomes, were rising at a rate of
22.5 billion dollars, after having fallen by 4.9 billion in
October.
</P>
<P>
Americans' disposable income, the amount left after paying
taxes, rose by 0.5 percent in the month following a small 0.1
percent gain in October.
</P>
<P>
After adjusting for inflation, disposable income rose by 0.3
percent in November after declining 0.2 percent in October.
</P>
<P>
The personal savings rate in the U.S., savings as a percentage
of disposable income, held steady at 5 percent in November, the
same level as October.
</P>
<P>
The report said that U.S. Consumer spending was up by 0.5
percent in November, down from a 0.7 percent gain in October.
</P>
<P>
After inflation adjustments, consumer spending was up by 0.3
percent in November after a 0.4 percent October increase.
</P>
<P>
The big increase in personal consumption spending reflected
strength in purchases of services but sales of both durable and
nondurable goods also showed advances.
</P>
<P>
Many analysts believe consumer spending, which accounts for
two-thirds of total economic activity, holds the key to whether
the U.S. economy continues to grow at a modest rate through 1997
or whether slowdown snowballs into something worse such as an
outright recession.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government reported last week that nation's gross
domestic product rose at an annual rate of just 2.1 percent during
the third quarter of this year after a 4.7 percent surge in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
But the consumer spending rose a barely perceptible 0.5
percent, the poorest showing in nearly five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
