<HEADLINE> Netanyahu, Arafat May Meet Tonight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat may meet tonight to conclude the Hebron
redeployment agreement, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic breakthrough in the talks between the Israelis
and Palestinians came this afternoon when Netanyahu joined the
negotiations held at the King David Hotel in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mahmoud Abbas, Arafat's deputy and Palestinian top
negotiator, came from the Gaza Strip to participate in the
talks, which were a continuation of Sunday night's Marathon
talks in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and visiting U.S. special Middle East coordinator
Dennis Ross took an active role in the night-long intensive
negotiations held at Arafat's Gaza office and lasted until
early this morning.
</P>
<P>
Both Arafat and Ross expressed cautious optimism following
the talks, but Ross admitted that difference remained between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
PNA Finance Minister Mohammed Nashashibi said today that
there has been progress in all directions in Sunday night's
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Nashashibi told reporters that the negotiators are working on
a package deal involving other issues in addition to Hebron, but
he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Sources in both delegations said that Netanyahu and Arafat
could meet as soon as tonight to conclude the agreement on the
Israeli army's redeployment in the disputed West Bank town.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Arafat told reporters in Gaza that a meeting
between himself and the Israeli prime minister could take place
"later today."
</P>
<P>
Progress in the negotiations was reported earlier today
before Netanyahu and Abbas joined in to make a final push to
conclude the agreement before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the breakthrough is a package deal Ross has
been working on, which includes Israel's commitment to further
redeploy its troops in the West Bank following the redeployment
in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Under the package deal, Israel also would agree to hold final
status talks on the West Bank and other issues a few weeks after
the conclusion of the Hebron redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that Netanyahu is holding a special
cabinet meeting at this hour to brief cabinet ministers on the
outcome of the latest negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ross, who flew to Egypt today to brief Egyptian
officials on the latest development in Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations, is flying back to Israel, and is due to arrive
here in the coming hours.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Abbas returned to the Gaza Strip to report
to Arafat on the result of today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
The report said that if Arafat accepts the package deal, a
meeting between the Palestinian leader and the Israeli premier
would take place tonight at the Erez Checkpoint between Israel
and the Gaza Strip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
