<HEADLINE> Pig Heart Transplant in India Turns Out to Be Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A recent controversial pig
heart transplant on a human being by an Indian doctor turned out
to be a case of fraud aimed at securing publicity for the doctor
himself, Press Trust of India reported today.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old doctor, identified as Dhani Ram Baruah, had
claimed that he had successfully transplanted a pig heart to a
patient who suffered from incurable heart disease in a clinic in
India's Assam state earlier last week.
</P>
<P>
Kamala Kalita, Assam state health minister, today made a
statement to the state assembly, saying that it was a case of
fraud.
</P>
<P>
He said Baruah first claimed before the press, which was also
recorded on video, that he had performed the transplant and then
gave a written declaration to a government-appointed inquiry
committee that he did not performed the transplant.
</P>
<P>
This proved that the doctor "plotted to cheat," the minister
noted.
</P>
<P>
The minister assured the local house that necessary action
would be taken against Baruah "who wanted to get publicity by
spreading false news."
</P>
<P>
Kalita said in view of the news about the pig heart transplant
creating a worldwide sensation and raising controversy, the issue
was investigated by a government-appointed inquiry committee under
the health establishment act of the state.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
