<HEADLINE> Three Million Children Live in Jobless Homes in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Over three million children in
Britain live in a home where no one has a job, an increase of
400,000, 15 percent up since the last general election, the
opposition Labor Party says Monday.
</P>
<P>
The number of jobless two-parent homes has remained almost
static since the 1992 election at 500,000 while the number of
unemployed single parents has gone up by 220,000, or 27 percent
and now stands close to one million.
</P>
<P>
There are 1.7 million children in single-parent jobless
households compared to 1.1 million children with two parents
without jobs.
</P>
<P>
Labor says that the increase of the number of children living
in jobless homes is mainly due to rising unemployment among single
mothers, and now more than half of lone mothers are out of work.
</P>
<P>
The figures were "a shocking indictment of failed Tory policies"
and "the best Christmas present ministers could give youngsters is
the chance of a job for their parents," said Labor employment
spokesman Peter Hain.  
</P>
