<HEADLINE> ICRC Makes Emergency Appeal for 1997 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December (Xinhua) -- The International Committee of the
Red Cross (ICRC) has made an emergency appeal for its 1997 budget
of 572 million U.S. dollars while it still lacks a total of 41
million dollars for 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to an ICRC press release issued here today, of the
total budget, 107 million dollars will be used for its
headquarters budget, 465 million dollars will go for the field
budget. The field budget shows an increase of eight percent
compared to the initial budget for 1996, without taking possible
operations in Zaire into account.
</P>
<P>
The largest proportion of the 1997 field budget is assigned to
Africa, with about 181.5 million dollars, accounting for over one
third of the field budget. 20 percent of the budget (about 98.5
million dollars) will go to Eastern Europe and Central Asia. The
operations in Rwanda alone will take nearly 52 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
As for a shortage of funds for the current year, the
Geneva-based ICRC says that a total of 41 million dollars is still
needed to close the 1996 accounts without a deficit. Moreover,
pledges amounting to 46 million dollars still have to be honored.
ICRC is concerned that it will probably face an unprecedented
financial situation at the end of 1996 if donors do not respond
immediately to close the gap. 
</P>
</TEXT>
