<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Returned PAP Still Facing Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 23 (Xinhua) -- After being returned to
power as 47 of its candidates, already a majority in the 83-seat
Parliament, won their walkovers on the Nomination Day today, the
ruling People's Action Party (PAP) of Singapore is gearing itself
up to dampen the by-election strategy by the opposition camp and
expand its victory.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts here pointed out, however, that although
there is no question about the PAP's overwhelming victory in the
eighth general election since the country's independence in 1965,
its battles against the opposition -- the Workers' Party (WP), the
Singapore Democratic Party (SDP), and the Singapore People's Party
(SPP) in particular -- in certain single-seat wards may not be as
easy as one imagines.
</P>
<P>
The opposition camp was believed to be again employing the
strategy of by-election effect this time, as it fielded a total of
only 39 candidates, with 38 from the five opposition parties and
one as an independent candidate.
</P>
<P>
With this tactics, the opposition is attempting to take
advantage of the logic by some voters that given the PAP enjoying
the majority in the legislature, maybe it's better to have one or
two more opposition members in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
In other words, by contesting fewer than half of the seats and
conceding government to the PAP on Nomination Day, the opposition
gave voters one reason fewer to vote for the PAP in their
respective constituencies.
</P>
<P>
The opposition used the strategy in the 1991 general election,
in which it won a record large number of four seats in the House,
while the PAP suffered a lowest support rate of 60.97 percent.
</P>
<P>
To defuse the opposition strategy, the PAP candidates, since
last year, have been presenting various estate improvement plans,
or housing upgrading plans as bottom-up initiatives and have made
these promises part of a job to be undertaken by the proposed
Community Development Councils (CDCs), or as is called, the local
government.
</P>
<P>
Some observers said that given the pragmatic attitude of the
voters, and now that the stakes in each constituency are higher
than ever before, it is obvious that the choice of a Member of
Parliament (MP) will have a direct impact on voters' life.
Therefore, they believe the PAP has found an effective counter to
the by-election strategy in this local-election effect.
</P>
<P>
However, some others pointed out that estate improvement,
redevelopment and upgrading programs might not benefit all voters
uniformly, as they might be irrelevant to people in private homes
or new estates.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the campaign strategies, the political analysts
said more attention should be paid to the fights in such
single-seat constituencies as Hougang, Potong Pasir, MacPherson,
and Bukit Gombak, where "close battles", as they described, could
be staged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Returned PAP Still Facing Challenges in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
They also noted to their surprise that the opposition should
manage to come up with six teams to rival the PAP in six of the
total of the 15 Group Representation Constituencies (GRCs).
</P>
<P>
The straight fight between the five-member team of the Workers'
Party led by Secretary-General J.B. Jeyaretnam against the PAP
team led by Education Minister Lee Yock Suan in the Cheng San GRC
would be something worth attention, they said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, they were quick to add that since not a single
opposition team survived in the GRCs in the 1991 election, they
were not sure of the fate of these opposition team candidates this
time.
</P>
<P>
But it is true that this is the first time ever the opposition
managed to put up so many teams in the GRCs' fight. If, and only
if, one of the opposition teams should win, it would be something
of a decisive significance, though the chances of this happening
are not great, they said.
</P>
<P>
Some observers also noted that of the 24 new candidates fielded
by the PAP, all were well-educated with university degrees and
have an average age of 41, reflecting the PAP claim that this
would be the team to lead Singapore well into the 21st century,
while by comparison, none of the opposition parties comes up with
a comparable team as such.
</P>
<P>
Besides, although the opposition parties might launch attacks
on certain PAP policies, none of them offered any set of policies
as comprehensive and practical as those of the PAP to take
Singapore into the next century. This is a fatal wound for them,
the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew said earlier today that voting
this time will have a deeper significance for everyone. This is
because the stakes are higher as the voters have to decide whether
the team voted in will be able to run the town council and work
with a Community Development Council.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he warned new voters, especially young voters, to
take their votes seriously, saying that more importantly, the
value of one's estate could be affected by a wrong vote or a
protest vote.  
</P>
