<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Cotton Output Declines: Committee Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The world's cotton
production is estimated at 18.87 million tons in 1996/97, 1.2
million tons less than last season, said the Washington-based
International Cotton Advisory Committee.
</P>
<P>
In a monthly report issued here today, the committee noted that
the world cotton consumption for the year is estimated at 18.89
million tons, an increase of 400,000 tons over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The Cotlook A Index, an indicator of average world cotton
prices, rose from 75 cents per pound in mid-November to nearly 80
cents in mid-December, reflecting lower expectations for cotton
production in Pakistan, Uzbekistan, Greece, Paraguay, Turkmenstan
and Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the increase in the past month, prices during
the current season are expected to be lower on average than during
1994/95 and 1995/96 which was about 94 cents and 85.6 cents per
pound separately, the report said.
</P>
<P>
World cotton production is expected to reach 19.65 million tons
and consumption 19.52 million tons in 1997/98, therefore, keeping
world supply and demand roughly in balance at the current price
level, indicating little pressure on cotton prices. Thanks to
China's lower net imports which are expected to remain at least as
low in 1997/98 as in 1996/97, the 1997/98 average Cotlook A Index
is estimated at 78 cents per pound, not statistically different
from the estimate of 77 cents for the current year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
