<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Former South Korean Presidents Not to Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Former South Korean Presidents
Chun Doo-hwan and Roh Tae-woo decided today that they will not
make appeals to the Supreme Court against the Seoul High Court's
ruling over their respective sentences for the mutiny, treason and
bribery case.
</P>
<P>
So far, of the 15 defendants involved in the mutiny and treason
case, only Chun and Roh will not appeal to the country's highest
court.
</P>
<P>
However, since the South Korean prosecution decided to appeal
sentences, the Supreme Court is likely to start its deliberation
beginning early next year and is expected to make the final
judgment around April.
</P>
<P>
On December 16, the Seoul High court commuted the death
sentence to life imprisonment for Chun and 22 years and six months
in prison to 17 years in prison for Roh.
</P>
<P>
It also fined Chun 265.7 million U.S. dollars and Roh 316.6
million dollars, representing the bribes they allegedly received
while in office.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Seoul High Court also commuted the prison terms
of 4-10 years to 3.5-8 years for the 13 former South Korean
officers, including former First Army Corps Commander Hwang
Young-si, who helped Chun and Roh in their quest for power.
</P>
<P>
In the first trial on August 26 this year, the Seoul District
Court sentenced Chun to death and Roh to 22 years and six months
in prison respectively on charges of mutiny, treason and bribery.
</P>
<P>
The mutiny and treason charges stem from the roles played by
Chun and Roh as well as their cronies in the military coup on
December 12, 1979 and the suppression of the civil uprising in
Kwangju, capital of South Korea's South Cholla Province, on May
18, 1980.
</P>
<P>
The 15 defendants were arrested at the end of last year after
President Kim Young-sam called for the enactment of a special bill
paving the way to punish them for past wrongdoing without regard
for the statue of limitations.
</P>
<P>
Chun seized power on August 27, 1980 and ruled the nation until
February 1988. He was followed by Roh who stepped down in February
1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
