<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Repeats Refusal of Israel's "Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias Hrawi
stressed here today a rejection of Israel's "Lebanon first"
proposal and its varieties, including the suggestion of deploying
Jordanian and Egyptian peacekeeping forces in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi made the remarks as receiving representatives of the
Arab News Agencies Union (ANAU), who ended a three-day annual
meeting in the Lebanese capital Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
The president was quoted by Rafik Shlala, vice chairman of
the ANAU and director of the state-run Lebanese National News
Agency, as saying "We never accept these suggestions."
</P>
<P>
He said "the Lebanese army is present and it is ready to fully
play its role."
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that as soon as the Israeli occupation forces
withdraw from south Lebanon, the Lebanese army "guarantees the
tranquility and stability" on the Lebanese-Israeli border and
"prevents any shot and bombardment" at northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi repeated his country's refusal of stopping the
resistance against the Israeli occupation before the Jewish state
pulls its forces out of the Lebanese territories.
</P>
<P>
He said that Lebanon will be the last Arab country reaching
peace with Israel, noting that "this is not out of fear but faith."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Internal Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani suggested
last week that a multinational peacekeeping force including
Egyptian and Jordanian contingents be deployed in the occupied
border enclave in south Lebanon after an Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Both Egypt and Jordan are bound to the Jewish state by
peace treaties, and Kahalani's exclusion of Damascus was
perceived by Beirut as an attempt to undercut Syria's role.
</P>
<P>
Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, has a 35,000-strong
force spreading over two thirds of Lebanon's lands.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied a border strip in south Lebanon in late 1970s
and unilaterally turned the 1,100-square-kilometer strip,
stretching from the Mediterranean coast to the west eastward to
Mount Hermon, into Israel's "security zone" in 1985.
</P>
<P>
After taking power last June, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu raised the "Lebanon first" proposal, under which the
Jewish state will pull its forces out of the buffer zone after a
security arrangement is mapped out with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon categorically refused the proposal, saying that it
was aimed at driving a wedge between Lebanon and Syria, the
last two Arab countries still in a state of war with the
Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
