<HEADLINE> S. Africa's De Klerk Calls New Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 23 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's former
President De Klerk said today that the new Constitution has paved
way for national reconciliation, nationhood and a better life.
</P>
<P>
In his Christmas message to the nation, De Klerk, who is
currently leader of the opposition National Party, said the
promulgation of the final constitution was the best Christmas
gift, providing a framework within which South Africans could be
confident of respect for their cultural differences.
</P>
<P>
"But our greatest challenge is to refrain from one-sided
interpretations which serve only specific interests while pushing
aside the interests of others," said De Klerk.
</P>
<P>
The National Party, a major political organization of the
South African whites and former partner of the coalition
government headed by Nelson Mandela, withdrew from the government
in May due to its political differences with the African National
Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
