<HEADLINE> S. African Farmers Urged Not to Shoot Elephants, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Transvaal
Agricultural Union (TAU) has called on farmers not to shoot
elephants or hippos which damaged land and houses.
</P>
<P>
TAU official Gert Ehlers said in Pietersburg at the weekend
that complaints had been received from farmers along the Limpopo
River bordering Zimbabwe that elephants had been breaking through
dilapidated international fences, causing damage to farms and
sub-tropical fruits.
</P>
<P>
The elephants also caused damage to water tanks, and
surrounding villages were complaining that the jumbos were
endangering their lives.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, large numbers of hippos restricted to isolated pools two
years ago, who were being fed during years of drought, had moved to
greener pastures after recent good rains and were now found in pools
they had inhabited more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
The wandering hippos posed a danger to uninformed people
visiting the region, and caused havoc on irrigated land on river
banks.
</P>
<P>
Nature conservationists recently claimed that farmers were allowed
to hunt hippos on their farms. However, Ehlers said he seriously
questioned these allegations because members of organized agriculture
fully supported the TAU's commitment to nature conservation and its
policy of farming in harmony with nature.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he called on farmers who were experiencing problems
with animals on their farms to contact the TAU's nature conservation
and game committees to solve the problems.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Department of Environmental Affairs and
Tourism said earlier that the Department would give assistance to
farmers who preferred that the animals be removed and resettled
elsewhere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
