<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-23 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Egypt Affirm Progress on Hebron Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Middle East mediator Dennis
Ross and Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said today that a
deal on Hebron is near though the Palestinians and Israelis still
need to clear the way ahead.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy will return to Israel tonight after meeting with
Moussa and Osama el-Baz, the chief political adviser to President
Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Ross told reporters that Palestinian and
Israeli negotiators were trying hard to strike a deal on Hebron,
the last West Bank city from which Israel is supposed to pull out
troops last March under the autonomy accords.
</P>
<P>
"The negotiators, I think, are working hard. There is still
work to be done. But I think there is a new energy in the
negotiations," Ross said.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. envoy did not say if an agreement can be reached
before Christmas on Wednesday. His last mediation effort collapsed
in October.
</P>
<P>
"I am hopeful that we can see an agreement soon, but I am not
going to predict when."
</P>
<P>
Moussa also expressed optimism about the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"It's clear that progress has been made on Israeli army
redeployment in Hebron and other topics," he told reporters,
adding that Egypt has contacted the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said there are some ideas "acceptable to the
Palestinians and Israelis" on this score, noting that all these
points are still under discussion.
</P>
<P>
Calling Egypt "a pillar of the peace process," Ross said he
came here to learn its opinion on the Hebron talks.
</P>
<P>
Ross had separate meetings with Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu Saturday and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
over the weekend, before his arrival here early today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Egypt's Middle East News Agency learned from sources
close to the talks that Palestinian-Israeli agreement is likely
to be signed during the coming few hours on pending issues.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have so far reached agreement on two points, the
reopening of Shuhada Street and Hussein Market, and the formation
of joint Palestinian-Israeli patrols.
</P>
<P>
Contacts are taking place at present to bring closer
differences on the arming of Palestinian police.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the Palestinian insistence on a presence at the
Ibrahimi Mosque, it was suggested to set up a liaison office at
the mosque to regulate contacts between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
In case a written agreement is reached, it will be supported by
an American or an American-Egyptian letter of guarantee to make
sure that Palestinians and Israelis live up to their word in
implementing the remaining part of the peace accords.
</P>
<P>
It is suggested that the agreement and annexed protocols be
signed at the Eretz check-point between Israel and Palestinian
self rule areas.
</P>
<P>
The agreement calls for the implementation of the final stage
of the peace accords according to the previous timetable agreed
upon at Oslo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
