<HEADLINE> S. African Archbishop Calls for National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 23 (Xinhua) -- South African Archbishop
Winston Ndungane said today that the elimination of political
differences and poverty should be given priority in the coming
year.
</P>
<P>
In his Christmas message, Ndungane, successor of Archbishop
Desmond Tutu, said churches in South Africa should give first
priorities to things that will safeguard national reconciliation,
solve massive poverty problems and promote a relationship of
"critical solidarity" with the government.
</P>
<P>
Referring to relations between churches and the government,
the Archbishop said churches must supervise the government to be
equal and fair to the poor people.
</P>
<P>
Ndungane also welcomed the recent declaration made by the
United Nations that the 1997-2007 decade would be internationally
dedicated to the eradication of poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
