<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Returns to Kremlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today returned to the Kremlin and resumed his work after a
rehabilitation period following a heart by-pass surgery last month.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin arrived at his office in the Kremlin this morning at
about 09:40 Moscow time. Getting out from his car, he chatted
briefly with reporters, who had been waiting for him at the
entrance.
</P>
<P>
"I am in a good mood. I feel fine, and I am ready for battle,"
said the Russian president in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin listed the payment of long-delayed wages and pensions,
problems of the armed services and Chechen settlement as his
priorities back at work.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the conviction that 1997 would "without doubt be
better than the outgoing year."
</P>
<P>
According to his spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky, the president
will have working meetings with chief of the presidential
administration Anatoly Chubais and Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin later today and on Tuesday, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, in a televised interview, Yeltsin said he would
return to the Kremlin on December 23, because "the country needs
an active and energetic president, particularly now."
</P>
<P>
The 65-year-old president had a heart bypass operation on
November 5, four months after his successful re-election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
