<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maputo to Improve Water Supply in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Water supply is expected to be
improved in Mozambique's capital of Maputo where only 60 percent
of its two million residents have access to tap water, an official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Miguel Alves, general manager of the Maputo Water Authority,
said he is optimistic about the prospect as his company
would make better use of the Umbeluzi River and the Pequenos
Libombos Dam.
</P>
<P>
He said a new water pipe, which supplies water from the
Umbeluzi River to Maputo, would be built.
</P>
<P>
Another 60-kilometer pipeline network would be repaired to
provide water to the city's drought areas which had not been able
to have access to water during the last 10 years, according to
Alves.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, 45 fountains have been built to benefit
about 22,000 people.
</P>
<P>
And with the help of Chinese companies, 11 wells have been
dug in 1996. Another 50 are expected to be sunk in the coming
year, said the general manager. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
