<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR to Stop Food Aid to Liberian Refugees in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) will stop distributing food aid
to most of the 13,500 Liberian refugees in Ghana next year in a
bid to encourage the refugees to be self-reliant.
</P>
<P>
Chrysantus Ache, UNHCR Representative in Ghana, said in a
report reaching here today that the decision would be effective
starting January 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, he explained that "vulnerable refugee groups" such as
the elderly, children and young mothers may continue to benefit
from free food assistance.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, plans are under way for refugee repatriation on the
basis of willingness, said Ache. For example, plans of building
402 refugee homes in Krisan, Ghana, have been finalized, he said.
</P>
<P>
The refugees flooded into Ghana last May when renewed
factional fighting erupted in the Liberian capital of Monrovia
last April.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the 13,500 registered Liberian refugees living
in a camp near the Ghanaian capital of Accra, there are another
5,700 unregistered Liberian refugees living in the camps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
