<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tajik President, Opposition Leader Sign Peace Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Tajik President Emomali
Rakhmonov and leader of the United Tajik Opposition Sayed Abdullo
Nuri signed two documents here today, which are expected to end
the over-four-year civil war in Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
The two documents, an agreement on the results of the Moscow
negotiations and a protocol on the functions and powers of the
National Reconciliation Commission, were signed at Moscow's
President-Hotel in the presence of Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the sides will finally settle their
conflict by way of negotiations within 18 months.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a cease-fire will be announced for the period of the
talks. In addition, the document envisages a general amnesty and
exchange prisoners of war according to the principle "all for
all."
</P>
<P>
Under the protocol, the National Reconciliation Commission to
be established soon and headed by a representative of the
opposition will control the implementation of the agreement and
have some governmental powers.
</P>
<P>
The commission will have the right to participate in "reforming
the government" by way of incorporating its representatives into
the executive branch, including ministries, state agencies, local
government judicial and law enforcement bodies.
</P>
<P>
The commission will also take part in making amendments to the
existing constitution and in making preparations for the future
parliamentary elections in the Central Asian republic.
</P>
<P>
The issue of the commission membership will be discussed at the
next round of inter-Tajik talks scheduled for January 5 in Tehran,
Iran
</P>
<P>
Initially, the sides were expected to sign a final agreement on
Thursday, as the document had been initiated by Rakhmonov and Nuri
in Afghanistan on December 10 and 11.
</P>
<P>
But several days before the Moscow meeting scheduled to start
on Thursday, the opposition insisted on making some changes to the
already agreed text.
</P>
<P>
The opposition demanded that the commission should receive its
powers from the bodies of supreme power, including the Presidency
and legislature. The powers, according to them, should include
creation of a coalition government for the transitional period.
</P>
<P>
The government side made some compromise, agreeing, mainly, to
grant some governmental powers to the commission.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the sides finally reached agreement on signing of the two
documents.
</P>
<P>
Praising the accords after the signing ceremony, Chernomyrdin
said the agreements "reflect the wishes of the whole people of
Tajikistan, tired of war and internal feuds." He participated in
the Tajik talks as a mediator.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia will always do its best to secure steady
peace and national accord in Tajikistan, expressing confidence
that both sides would have "enough wisdom and will to implement
the important decisions."
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin said that Russia will continue
to provide assistance to the peace process in Tajikistan, hopes
that the Moscow accords "lay a form foundation for inter-Tajik
settlement." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
