<HEADLINE> Kenya Committed to Eradicating Weeds in L. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan minister today
assured people that Kenya is committed to eradicating the rapidly
spreading water hyacinth in Lake Victoria.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Environment and Natural Resources Henry Kosgey
made the remarks today as he was touring beaches in Kisumu,
western Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan official said his government is concerned about the
weeds which have almost blocked the lake, adding that Lake
Victoria is "the lifeline" to about 37 million people living
around the region in the three East African countries --
Uganda, Tanzania and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
He announced that Kenya Agricultural Research Institute (KARI)
will start training 100 local people who will rear the weevils
currently being reared at KARI Kibos center.
</P>
<P>
Kosgey disclosed that the weevils, which are currently
breeding in their thousands and will soon multiply into millions,
will be introduced into the lake early next year.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the local people that the World Bank will
soon release 24 million U.S. Dollars for the Lake Victoria
Environmental Management.
</P>
<P>
The money is part of 70 million U.S. Dollars the bank pledged
to Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda to help eradicate the weeds in the
lake.
</P>
<P>
KARI, which helped eradicate another weed called salvinia
molesta from lake Naivasha in the 1980s, is implementing a
program to wipe out the water hyacinth from the lake through
biological method. 
</P>
</TEXT>
