<HEADLINE> EU to Reconsider Ban on S. Africa's Ostrich Meat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
has reconsidered lifting the ban on imports of live ostriches and
ostrich meat from South Africa before February 15 next year.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from the South African Press Association
today, the ban was imposed by EU's Standing Veterinary Committee
in early November after an outbreak of Congo fever at the
Oudtshoorn abattoir in Western Cape Province.
</P>
<P>
Last week, a South African delegation, led by Director of
Veterinary Public Health of the Agriculture Department Gedeon
Bruckner, visited Brussels to discuss the implications of the ban
with members of the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
In terms of a joint statement issued by the Department and the
National Ostrich Producers Association, the EU had been asked to
differentiate between the ban proposed for ostrich meat and that
for live ostriches because there was an immediate and urgent need
to resume the export of ostrich meat.
</P>
<P>
"It was also pointed out there was no scientific reason to
discriminate between ostrich meat, beef or mutton from South
Africa and (meat) from the rest of Africa or other parts of the
world where the disease occurs," said the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
