<HEADLINE> Six Killed in US Cargo Plane Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Six people were killed in
the Sunday crash of a U.S. DC-8 cargo plane when it was flying
through freezing rain and smashed into a mountain in southwest
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
The plane was on a test flight Sunday evening from Greensboro,
North Carolina, to Wilmington, Ohio, when it crashed and exploded
in a remote forest near the Virginia-West Virginia state line.
</P>
<P>
Authorities said three crew members and three mechanics on
board the plane were killed and rescue teams began removing the
bodies off the mountain today.
</P>
<P>
The wreckage was found scattered over 1,000 meters up the
mountain, about five kilometers northwest of Narrows.
</P>
<P>
Bob McIntosh, the lead investigator on the scene for the
National Transportation Safety Board, said the plane had made the
first leg of the test flight from Ohio to North Carolina on
Saturday. It was returning to Ohio when it crashed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Investigation was underway and investigators are trying to get
the flight recorder to help determine the cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
The plane belonged to Airborne Express' subsidiary ABX Air,
based in Wilmington, Ohio. ABX Air had just bought the used plane.
</P>
</TEXT>
