<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Mideast Peace Process Deadlocked But </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Middle East peace process
became deadlocked in 1996 despite tremendous efforts to push it
ahead, but signs show that it is still on track.
</P>
<P>
At one stage, the peace train was gaining speed last
spring. The Palestinians held their first ever election to choose
the self-rule leadership in January.
</P>
<P>
And the then Israeli ruling Labor party dropped its opposition
to an independent Palestinian state in April, one day after the
Palestine National council revised its anti-Israeli
stand. Meanwhile, the Syrians and Israelis were also geared to
speed up their negotiations over the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
However, the tangible progress was mingled with stepped up
violence and terrorist activities designed to derail the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Four suicide bombings inside Israel in February and March and
Israeli military operations in south Lebanon in retaliation for
Hezbullah rocketing in April all served to brake the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, when the Likud-led hardline government regained
power in June, the future of the peace march became bleaker.
</P>
<P>
The new Israeli government headed by Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu has never hesitated to air its reluctance to go ahead
with the "land for peace" formula, which was internationally
recognized and accepted by the previous Labor government.
</P>
<P>
Nor has the government tried to hide its intention to change
the rule of the game. It blatantly said "no" to returning the
Golan to Syria, to negotiation over Jerusalem with the
Palestinians and to establishing an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
This came out as far more than a mere rhetoric. The new
government promptly lifted a freeze on Jewish settlement
expansion, confiscated more Arab lands and banned official
Palestinian activities in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Israeli troops redeployment from Hebron was
delayed, with other issues such as safe passage between Gaza and
the West Bank, the release of Palestinian prisoners and Israeli
pullout from rural areas of the West Bank, pending for
solution. All these are embodied in the Oslo II accord and
supposed to be solved ahead of the most thorny final status
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
There is no headway seen on the Syria and Lebanon tracks
either. Damascus made Israel's territorial concession a
precondition for the resumption of peace talks, while Lebanon
rejected outright the "Lebanon First Option" dished out by
Israel. Efforts were made to break the ice, but no progress was in
evidence.
</P>
<P>
Not only the Palestinians but also people in the Arab world as
a whole are disappointed or frustrated. They lost no opportunity
to warn Israel against any backoff, or to face icy ties with its
Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
They hope the United States would come to tame Israel, its
strategic alliance in the region, but Washington seems less
prepared to amend its bias toward Israel. The EU and Russia are
invited to play a greater role but neither admits intention to
challenge the U.S. leading position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-23 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Mideast Peace Process Deadlocked But </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Despite the stalemate in the peace process, no party concerned
has declared a dead end to it. Netanyahu even made promise to
implement the Oslo accords -- though reluctantly as they have
already passed the Knesset (parliament) and become binding law
with worldwide backing. Going back on his words not to meet Yasser
Arafat, he has so far shaken hands twice with the Palestinian
leader.
</P>
<P>
Following the bloody shootout in September between Israeli
soldiers and Palestinian police, the prime minister ordered the
Israeli team to negotiate redeployment from Hebron, the only West
Bank city still under Israeli control.
</P>
<P>
Although these facts are insufficient to ease Arab mistrust and
suspicion, they might have proved that neither Israel nor the
Palestinians want to return to war and bloodshed. However, it is
naive to believe there would be a big jump forward, observers said.
</P>
<P>
It is well known that Netanyahu's Likud party has long been
advocating "peace for peace" instead of "land for peace." That
formula still seems to serve as a basis for Israel's policy, which
Netanyahu may not easily change, because he has to measure
carefully harsh responses from his far-right coalition partners,
even if he himself sees it necessary, observers noted.
</P>
<P>
With no date set for resuming Israeli-Syrian peace talks, the
on-and-off Israeli-Palestinian negotiations would take a time
longer than expected. Even if the Oslo accords remain valid, the
process of implementation would still be difficult. As for the
final status negotiations, scheduled to conclude in 1999, either
side sees no possible bound to the bargain over Jerusalem,
refugees, borders and Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
The most discouraging sign is the confidence-building process
suffered setbacks. The September bloody confrontation, which
killed dozens and wounded a thousand, rekindled the deeply rooted
hatred and distrust between Israelis and Arabs.
</P>
<P>
The border closure since March inflicted a loss of 6 million
U.S. dollars a day to the Palestinian self-rule areas and fueled
anti-Israeli sentiment in the occupied land and elsewhere in the
Arab world.
</P>
<P>
The Arab outcry and warning didn't work well as Israel refused
to bow to pressure. The Europeans, eager to have a bigger say in
the Middle East, have failed to corner Israel to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
Washington, reluctant to risk a rupture with Israel, has tried
carefully to avoid offending the Jewish state. President Bill
Clinton is expected to take concrete measures to salvage the
faltering peace process in his second term of office, but it
remains to be seen how the reshuffled U.S. administration will act.
</P>
<P>
Some Arab scholars believe that real changes, if any, will come
from within Israel. They pin hopes on a possible national unity
government in Israel involving the Labor party, or the next
nationwide election scheduled for the year 2000. But they cannot
tell for sure what is to happen next morning.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process may not go in reverse in 1997,
observers said, but the prospect for a quick breakthrough may be
dim as well. Continuing the peace march requires greater efforts,
patience and self-restraint, they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Denies Provision of Arms to Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- France today denied an
accusation by Zairean rebels that it has provided arms to Zairean
government troops for launching a counter-offensive against the
Tutsi Banyamulenges.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry vice-spokesman Yves Doutriaux said that
France is strictly observing an arms embargo against Zaire as
decided by the European Union in 1993.
</P>
<P>
"In consequence, the French authorities have neither provided
any military aid, nor authorized any export of war material,"
said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Zairean rebel leader Laurent-Desire Kabila said that Zairean
government forces began a counter-offensive against the rebels in
the Bunia region near the Ugandan border in northeast Zaire last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He accused France of "preparing" for the counter-offensive,
saying that "Mobutu receives a military aid from France."
</P>
<P>
The rebels have been controlling a 500-kilometer-long strip
land bordering Uganda, Rwanda and Burundi for two months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
