<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-23 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian PM Maps out Furture Development Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian government led by
Prime Minister Kamal al-Ganzouri today confirmed its abidance by
extending reform and development to map out a better life for the
country in the future.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri delivered the government's second policy statement
before the People's Assembly, stressing the government's
commitment to implementing the strategy on development of Egypt
till year 2000, easing burden on the citizens and solving their
problems immediately.
</P>
<P>
The statement, which covers all ministries' development plans,
spotlights the details of implementing a line of national projects
including the project on Upper Egypt development.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri said the project, taking up 58 percent of Egypt's
land, will start January at a cost of 300 billion Egyptian pounds
(8,820 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
It will provide 250,000 job opportunities, he said, noting that
the project include setting up 25 heavy industries zones.
</P>
<P>
Gigantic projects will be implemented in Sinai and southern
part of the Nile Valley, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said 1997 is described to be the private sector year in
which investment in airports, roads and electricity stations will
be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
The statement also deals with the Ministry of Tourism's plans
to attract 4.2 million tourists next year. It said that the
government will provide all facilities to promote tourism in the
26 governorates.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to cut down the inflation rate, which hit
7 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
To activate exportation, the prime minister said that various
incentives were provided, including equal treatment of
export-oriented output with the production of free zones,
elimination of all fees on export inspection and reduction of
freight costs.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the various facilities, international investment
in Egypt has increased and the Paris Club has rewritten off the
third tranche of Egypt's foreign debt, he added.
</P>
<P>
Throughout 1996, applications for 4,996 projects were approved,
the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri reviewed the great efforts exerted by the government
to get out of the narrow valley and seek new horizons via the
strategy which started since President Hosni Mubarak took office
in 1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
