<HEADLINE> NATO's Supreme Commander in Europe to Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- NATO's Supreme Allied
Commander in Europe (SACEUR), American General George Joulwan,
said today he would retire from the position in the spring of 1997.
</P>
<P>
A news release from NATO's Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers
Europe (SHAPE), based in Mons, Belgium, said that no date has yet
been set for a change of command and no replacement has been named
for the NATO top general.
</P>
<P>
It said that General Joulwan has notified the Secretary General
of NATO, the U.S. Secretary of Defense and the Chairman, Joint
Chiefs of Staff of his decision.
</P>
<P>
As SACEUR, General Joulwan has led the way in planning and
executing the NATO-led Implementation Force (IFOR) in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The press release said General would continue to serve as
SACEUR through the first six months of the Stabilization Force
(SFOR) mission in Bosnia, which started just a few days ago,
providing needed continuity until his replacement assumes command.
</P>
<P>
During his 36 years of active duty service to his country,
General Joulwan served at every level of command, platoon through
Army Corps, and served as Commander in Chief of two Unified
Commands -- the U.S. Southern Command in Panama and the U.S.
European Command in Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
