<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Elects New Socialist Party Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Georgi Parvanov was elected
today new leader of the Socialist Party at its 42nd Special
Session in succession to Zhan Videnov who resigned on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Parvanov, a history major from Sofia University and former
deputy chairman of the highest committee of the ruling party,
called on his party to consolidate union and live up to social
expectations.
</P>
<P>
The session also adopted the party's action plan for next year
and promised to solve the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Zhan Videnov became prime minister after the Socialist Party
won the general election in December 1994. But criticism for his
failure to meet reform targets became more and more vocal, and a
recent party confidence vote gave him only narrow backing, leading
to his recent declaration of resignation after foreign minister
Georgi Pirinski quitted last month.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the National Assembly has decided to
suspend Christmas holiday to deal with the resignation issue.
</P>
<P>
Its chairman, Blagovest Sendov, said that a special meeting
will be held on December 28 to decide on the matter. If Videnov's
resignation is passed, Parvanov will become the new prime minister
and form a new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
According to Bulgarian law, the majority party forms a new
cabinet if the resignation of a government is approved by the
National Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
