<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Economy on Downslope in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 24 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's economy was on the
downslope in 1996 from the peak of growth it reached the previous
year, exposing the vulnerability of its high-cost and
low-efficiency industry in the rapidly growing world trade.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Korea, South Korea's central bank, estimated the
growth of gross domestic product (GDP) at 6.9 percent for the
year, down both from the previous year's 9 percent and the
projected 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's current account deficit is expected to hit an
all-time record high of 22 billion U.S. dollars, compared with the
deficit of 8.95 billion dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Largely affected by the soaring current-account deficit, South
Korea's foreign exchange reserves declined from 32.71 billion
dollars at the end of last year to 32.23 billion dollars at the
end of October 1996.
</P>
<P>
The central bank attributed the spiraling current account
deficit mainly to poor exports performance.
</P>
<P>
During the first 10 months of the year, South Korea's exports
totaled 106.47 billion dollars, while imports amounted to 123.28
billion dollars, for a deficit of 16.81 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Slowing export growth, primarily because of the weakened
international competitiveness of the country's major export
products, has led to increasing stockpiles of manufactured goods
in corporate warehouses, which in turn has caused companies to
postpone or discard plans for investment in new equipment and
plants.
</P>
<P>
The semiconductor industry, for instance, was sound in terms of
technology and production, but weak in terms of price
competitiveness and the situation was more or less the same in the
information-telecommunications and automobile industries which
were also important to the nation's export structure.
</P>
<P>
In the third quarter of 1996, while the heavy industry grew
10.5 percent from a year earlier, the light industry, which was
once a growth leader, declined 3.7 percent from the same period
last year, expanding the bipolarization of industrial expansion.
</P>
<P>
The terms of trade have also worsened. While unit export prices
in the July-September period of the year fell 15.3 percent on
average from a year earlier, unit import prices only declined 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
High wages, prices and interest rates were the chief villains
of the high-cost and low-efficiency industrial structure. Over the
past 10 years, manufacturing labor costs have shot up 19.7 percent
per year on average whereas comparable wage increases in the
United States and Japan have shot up 2.8 percent and 14.1 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to figures provided by the National
Statistical Office (NSO), in the third quarter, South Korea's
manufacturing sector lost 84,000 jobs, raising the jobless rate
from 2 percent in 1995 to 2.1 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The country's inflation rate, as measured by consumer prices,
will reach 5 percent in 1996, up from last year's 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government will put top priority on economic stability in
1997 to help reduce the snowballing current account shortfalls and
inflationary pressure, the bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kesri Builds up Lead in Race for CPP Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 24 (Xinhua) -- India's Congress party
President Sitaram Kesri, trying to install himself as the
consensus leader of the Congress parliamentary party (CPP), has
emerged as the front-runner in the race.
</P>
<P>
The race began after former prime minister P.V. Narasimha Rao
resigned from the powerful CPP leadership on December 19 under
huge pressure from his own party, especially Kesri.
</P>
<P>
A meeting to choose a new CPP chief was originally scheduled
for December 23 but was later postponed to January 3 because of
differences over how to choose a successor.
</P>
<P>
Kesri supporters advocate that the party president should
become the consensus leader of the CPP while some other party
leaders and members of parliament insist that a new CPP chief
should be chosen by an election.
</P>
<P>
As the January 3 meeting approaches, some senior party leaders
have begun to rally behind Kesri and established contact with
members of the CPP.
</P>
<P>
Party insiders said senior leaders A.K. Antony, K. Karunakaran,
Balram Jakhar and Vijaybhaskar Reddy have taken an active part in
the consensus-building exercise, trying to convince partymen that
only "a single center of power" can now take the Congress party
onward.
</P>
<P>
Karunakaran, who never failed to snipe at former party chief
Narasimha Rao for holding two party positions, has been singing a
different tune. He is a member of the Congress Working Committee
(CWC), the supreme decision-making body of the party.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted as saying that these were not normal
circumstances and, therefore, there should be no talks at this
stage of "one man-one post."
</P>
<P>
The senior Congress party leader has apparently been telling
partymen that Kesri's drive to rejuvenate the party had gathered
momentum and so he should be trusted with the controls of the
party.
</P>
<P>
"The fire-fighting is on. These leaders are confident they can
clinch the deal in Kesri's favor," another senior leader
commented.
</P>
<P>
Kesri's lieutenants such as Tariq Anwar, Ahmed Patel and Ghulam
Nabi Azad too have been on the move, enlisting support for a
consensus on Kesri. As part of their consensus-building exercise,
they have been releasing many statements to the media, calling for
the unanimous election of Kesri.
</P>
<P>
It seems that Kesri's supporters have been deliberately
painting visions of a split in the party if two or more centers of
power are allowed to emerge.
</P>
<P>
So far, only senior party leaders Sharad Pawar and Rajesh Pilot
have indicated their intention to run for the new CPP leadership.
</P>
<P>
Some other hopefuls are watching the development and would
throw their hat in the ring only if conditions are favorable.
</P>
<P>
However, a CWC member once close to Rao expressed the view that
the former prime minister was active in trying to prevent Kesri's
emergence as the consensus candidate.
</P>
<P>
In a statement Monday, Pilot, who is believed to enjoy support
among younger Congress partymen, insisted that he would be a
candidate for the election of CPP leader.
</P>
<P>
Kesri supporters have reportedly agreed that the intervening
period between now and January 3 should be fully utilized to mount
pressure on all those who want to contest.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
