<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Linjiang Built into Base For Rhodiola Sachalinensis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Experts in China have
succeeded in artificially cultivating a mountain-side herb that
can treat heart diseases, TB and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
The success has been made in Linjiang City in North China's
Jilin Province, home of Rhodiola Sachalinensis, a traditional
Chinese herbaceous herb with the same curative effect as ginseng.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year the city was named "home of the Rhodiola
Sachalinensis" by the Agriculture Development Research Center
under the State Council.
</P>
<P>
At present, Linjiang is China's largest production and
processing base for Rhodiola Sachalinensis, which are scattered
across the Changbai Mountain, 1,700 to 2,300 meters above the sea
level.
</P>
<P>
As a combination of food and medicine, stems of the Rhodiola
Sachalinensis have curative effect for diabetes, TB and heart
diseases.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between Linjiang Forestry Bureau and Shenyang
Medical Institute in 1982 has resulted in the extension of an
artificial cultivation area for Rhodiola Sachalinensis, which has
spread down to 500 meters above the sea level.
</P>
<P>
Linjiang City has developed Rhodiola Sachalinensis production
by setting up 134 hectares of cultivation area, with a production
volume of 150 tons.
</P>
<P>
Tonics made of Rhodiola Sachalinensis have been exported to
more than 20 overseas countries and regions, including the United
States, Canada, Japan, the Republic of Korea, Singapore, Malaysia,
Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
An official at the city government said that Linjiang plans to
extend the plant base to 667 hectares.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
