<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Emerging Opportunities for African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The year 1996 has seen
political developments in Africa getting further for the better,
providing a prerequisite and chances for sustained development.
</P>
<P>
During the year, most of African countries have maintained
stability. General elections held in Benin, Uganda, Zambia, Ghana
and other countries have gone on fairly peacefully this year,
whereas large-scale clashes occurred in some countries during
elections in the late 1980s and early 1990s because western-style
''democracy''was practised there.
</P>
<P>
Hot spots in Africa, generally speaking, have died down or
are dying down although new strifes broke out in eastern Zaire.
Rival factions in Liberia agreed to cease-fire in July and
started disarming their forces in November.
</P>
<P>
Rebels in Sierra Leone have joined the government this month
after sealing a peaceful agreement earlier. Even in Somalia,
opposing factions began to sit down to work for peaceful
solutions to their conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Peace process in Angola has gone on quite well and a
government of national unity will be formed next January, ending
nearly 20 years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
In Algeria, north Africa, a national reconciliation program
was signed by 38 political parties and organizations for a
settlement of political crisis, restoration of national stability
and dispelling of terrorism in the country.
</P>
<P>
African countries, encouraged by economic progress in other
parts of the world, Southeast Asia in particular, are laying
emphasis on their economic development, and have reaped
successes.
</P>
<P>
According to the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa
(ECA), Gross Domestic Product (GDP) of Africa in 1995 reached 2.3
percent over the previous year and the growth rate is expected to
reach 4.5 percent in 1996. the World Bank predicted an annual
economic growth of 3.8 percent for Africa within the 10 coming
years.
</P>
<P>
The world community's awareness and recognition of Africa's
importance in the international arena will bring opportunity
for African development, observers here say.
</P>
<P>
In May, Chinese President Jiang Zemin's tour of six African
states further strengthened China's friendship, enhanced its
unity with African countries and laid foundations for cooperative
ties between China and Africa in a comprehensive way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
