<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Parks Fees in Zimbabwe Cut by 50 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The Department of National Parks
and Wildlife Management of Zimbabwe has slashed its fees and tariffs
by 50 percent in response to complaints by the tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Acting Director of National Parks and Wildlife Management Willas
Makombe said, in a statemnt on Monday, that a 50 percent discount on entry,
accommodation, water-based recreation and vehicle entry fees had been
effected to boost the growth of domestic and international tourism.
</P>
<P>
''The department is cognizant of the pricing structure obtaining
in the region and therefore will continue to monitor the tariffs so
as to keep in touch with the pricing structure levels within the
region,'' said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The entry charges to all national parks have been standardised
while the vehicle entry charge has been built into the overall entry
tariff and the categorisation of vehicle entry fees per national park
dropped.
</P>
<P>
The changes came in the wake of representations from the Zimbabwe
Tourism Authority which complained that the high fees and tariffs
charged at national parks were likely to harm the tourism sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
