<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China to Improve Health Conditions of Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 24 (Xinhua) -- A new plan to help 200,000
people with disabilities improve their health within five years
has been drawn up in south China's Guangdong Province to help
teach deaf children to speak and train children with low IQs,
according to an official in charge of the project.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the health conditions of 130,000
handicapped people underwent a marked improvement during the
Eighth Five-Year (1991-1995) plan, thanks to painstaking efforts
by the province's medical personnel.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that more than 60,000 handicapped people
have been given jobs, helping raise the employment rate of those
with disabilities in Guangdong to a record high 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said that various provincial rehabilitation programs have
been playing a more important role in improving disabled persons'
lives.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that the province also plans to develop more
systematic precautions against various epidemic diseases and to
find a way to reduce the rate of deformity-causing maladies among
the people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
