<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai: Modern City With 6000-Year History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Most Chinese regard Shanghai,
China's economic center, as the symbol of modern civilization
during much of this century, but not many know just how old it
really is.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists have found 77 ancient sites in Shanghai's 6,341
sq km that have helped them trace its history back several
millenia. Research has shown that there were primitive people
living on the land occupied by present-day Shanghai, which lies at
the mouth of the Yangtze River, as early as 6,000 years ago and
that they were living a comparatively stable life, thanks to the
favorable environment.
</P>
<P>
To commemorate the 10th anniversary of Shanghai's having been
named a historic city, the city is staging an exhibition at the
History Museum of Shanghai, where visitors can see the cultural
relics that have been dug up.
</P>
<P>
One expert says that the objects on display reflect Shanghai's
prosperity and level of civilization during different historical
periods.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition also shows many prominent figures, such as Sun
Yat-sen, Mao Zedong, and Zhou Enlai, all of whom left their mark
on the Shanghai landscape. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
