<HEADLINE> Jewish Settlers Reportedly Uneasy as Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of the 450
Jewish settlers in the West Bank city of Hebron Monday night
lobbied legislators in the Knesset (parliament) in a desperate
attempt to block an army redeployment agreement which appears to
be just round the corner, reported Israel Radio today.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest reports today, Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu and Palestinian Authority President Yasser
Arafat are scheduled to meet at Erez on the Israeli-Gaza border
this morning and sign the overdue agreement.
</P>
<P>
"If the agreement is signed as it is, it will be just a
matter of time before Jewish blood is spilled in the city," said
Moshe Ben-Zimra, a spokesman for the Hebron settlers, Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
None of the Hebron settlement activists had any information
on the agreement beyond what was reported in the media, but they
gave the impression that they thought the long-delayed agreement
would soon be signed.
</P>
<P>
"I feel that we have been deceived by (Prime Minister
Binyamin) Netanyahu," Ben-Zimra said. "He has not lived up to
his agreement with the voters."
</P>
<P>
Hebron settlement leader Noam Arnon said of the agreement,
"This is the first step toward the destruction of the Jewish
community in Hebron."
</P>
<P>
What particularly concerned Arnon were reports that Shuhada
Street, which goes from the Machpela Cave to Tel Rumeida, will
be open to Palestinian traffic. He said this will enable
drive-by shootings, attempts by Palestinian drivers to run over
Jews, and even the planting of car bombs on the main artery
serving what Arnon called the "Jewish ghetto."
</P>
<P>
"Netanyahu will go down in history as the prime minister who
led to the destruction of the Jewish settlement in Hebron,"
Arnon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
