<HEADLINE> Top Legislature to Review Seven Laws, Many Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Standing Committee of the
Eighth National People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislative
body, began to convene its seven-day 23rd session today to examine
seven draft laws and many other resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Qiao Shi, chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, presided over
the opening session.
</P>
<P>
According to an agenda passed at the meeting today, an
anti-corruption law, or the draft law on administrative
supervision, and the Hong Kong garrison law will be put to vote
for approval at the end of this session.
</P>
<P>
The draft amendments to the Criminal Law and draft Law on
National Defense will be submitted to the full session of the
National People's Congress to be held next March for deliberations
after further revisions.
</P>
<P>
Three draft resolutions on election of deputies to the Ninth
NPC (March 1998-March 2003), on election of Hong Kong deputies in
particular to the Ninth NPC, and on convocation of the Fifth
Plenum of the Eighth NPC, are to be under review.
</P>
<P>
Three new laws, the draft Trust Law, the draft Law on Exclusive
Economic Zone and Continental Shelf and the draft Law on Blood
Donation, were tabled for the first time with the legislative body
today.
</P>
<P>
Among others, two international conventions, respectively on
control of desertification in countries with severe drought or
desertification and especially in Africa and on prohibition of the
development, production, stockpiling and use of chemical weapons
and on their destruction as well as a treaty concerning boundary
between China and Kirghistan, proposed by the State Council for
adoption, are also to be discussed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
