<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Relics Discovered in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 24 (Xinhua) -- A number of ancient relics
dating back to the Warring States period (475-221 B.C.) have been
unearthed at a construction site in Chengdu, the capital of
Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
A total of 37 relics made of copper, iron, pottery, and wood,
were found in a more than 2,000-year-old tomb.
</P>
<P>
A bronze sword and a spear found in the tomb are thought to be
in the style of the Qin Dynasty (221-207 b.c), while a dagger-axe
seems to belong to the Shu Kingdom (a small country in the Warring
States period), causing scholars to believe that the tomb was
built just after the Qin Kingdom defeated Shu.
</P>
<P>
Scholars say they believe that the find will aid research on
the Warring States period and on how dynasties succeeded each
other. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
