<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras, Graf Undisputed World No. Ones (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Pete Sampras and Steffi Graf,
who survived personal traumas in the past year, consolidated their
status as undisputed world number ones on the tennis court.
</P>
<P>
Sampras had to spend the year struggling to come to forms when
his coach and close friend Tim Gullikson died of a brain tumor.
The illness and loss affected him deeply: he was blasted out of
the Australian Open by local boy Mark Philippousis, went down to
eventual Dutch winner Richard Krajicek in the quarter-finals at
the Wimbledon and lost to French Open winner Yevbeny Kafelnikov in
the semi-finals on the clay.
</P>
<P>
However, his time came at the U.S. Open and the final
elite-eight world championships, which helped him to finish the
year at the top of the world and made him join Jimmy Connors and
John McEnroe as the only players to finish No. one for four
straight years.
</P>
<P>
Graf, who was troubled by persistent injuries, is not the
irresistible force in the passing year. But her competitive steel
shone through in a year in which her overwhelming concern remained
the fate of her father Peter, released on bail last month after 15
months in jail on charge of evading tax on his daughter's earnings.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old German successfully overcame strife in her
personal life to finish the year atop the world rankings for
fourth year in a row, with victories in every Grand Slam she
entered.
</P>
<P>
She missed out only the Australian Open after surgery on her
foot. All this went on while Peter languished in prison. "It has
been a really long, long year," she said after winning the
season-ending Chase Championships. She also won the German Open
as well as at Indian Wells and Key Biscayne.
</P>
<P>
Graf needs only four Grand Slam titles to pass Margaret Court's
record of 24. With Monica Seles still failing to recapture the
magic she displayed before her courtside knife attack in 1993,
Graf could polish those off in 1997. The German now has also won
five WTA Championships and 102 WTA crowns.
</P>
<P>
Her compatriot Boris Becker bounced back into the big time in
the men's court, ending the year as he began it with victory and
fat check. The 29-year-old veteran, who had spent 13 years in
pro tennis, won his first Grand Slam tournament for five years at
the Australian Open in January and earned him a cool 1.875 million
U.S. dollars with victory in the Grand Slam Cup in December.
</P>
<P>
However, it was not all roses in between. A pulled muscle kept
the powerful German out of the French Open and an agonizing wrist
injury forced him to quit Wimbledon mid-match just as he was
getting into his booming stride through a favorable draw.
</P>
<P>
Andre Agassi's year was characterized with fragility. The
popular and normally ebullient American finished 1996 with boos
and whistles of disappointed fans ringing in his ears after
miserable performances at the ATP World Championships and at the
Grand Slam Cup. An Olympic gold was the only comfort but Agassi
admitted he lacked motivation and needed a break from the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras, Graf Undisputed World No. Ones (2-last) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The men's tennis ended the year on a dramatic note when France
beat Sweden 3-2 in the Davis Cup final, the first final ever to be
decided in the fifth set of the fifth rubber in the Cup's 96-year
history.
</P>
<P>
The tie also features the last appearance of Sweden's Stefan
Edberg, a peerless serve-and-volley exponent and a fine
advertisement for his sport.
</P>
<P>
Edberg, who would retire at the end of this season, notched up
41 tournament victories and six Grand Slam titles in an exemplary
13-year career.
</P>
<P>
Monica Seles, who returned to WTA tennis last year, had a
disappointing season, which was ended in pain and frustration when
her sore left shoulder forced her to quit the Chase Championships
in November.
</P>
<P>
After winning the Australian Open to start the season, Seles
tore a muscle in her left, serving shoulder and has struggled to
maintain her form since.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old Yugoslav-American lost in the quarter-finals at
the French Open and in the second round at the Wimbledon before
clawing her way to the U.S. Open where she lost to longtime rival
Graf.
</P>
<P>
Lindsay Davenport enjoyed a golden winning streak in the summer
with Olympic gold in Atlanta and a triumph in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
Davenport also joined with Seles, Mary Joe Fernandez and Linda
Wild to win the Fed Cup for the United States in Atlantic City
with a 5-0 victory over Spain.
</P>
<P>
Spaniards Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario and Conchita Martinez have
a disappointing year. Neither won a major title and both suffered
long periods of loss of form.
</P>
<P>
Sanchez-Vicario, who has grid, but not the array of the
strokes, finished the year twice the bridesmaid -- at the French
Open and Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
France's Mary Pierce, 1995 Australian Open champion and world
number three twelve months ago, had a free-fall and ended the year
down in 20th place in the rankings.
</P>
<P>
With the veteran struggling to keep their positions in the
rankings, players of the younger generation have appeared to be
impatient to catch up.
</P>
<P>
Martina Hingis, a 16-year-old Swiss school girl, has won two
WTA titles and finished the year at world No. 5. Described as the
"hottest property in tennis", Hingis also became the youngest
player to win the doubles at the French Open.
</P>
<P>
Russian Anna Kournikova made a sensational splash at the
U.S. Open by beating seeded Barbara Paulus of Austria. At the
European Indoor Championships in October, the 15-year-old beat
tough South African Amanda Coetzer.
</P>
<P>
The year of 1996 also saw the retirement of Japan's Kimiko Date
and Argentina's Gabriela Sabatini. The two players, both at 26,
left the tour with different reasons. Some think that with a new
ranking system for 1997, the two may consider that they have to
give ways to younger generation in the tour.
</P>
<P>
Under the new system which was unveiled by the WTA Tour in
November, Graf and Seles, who have been plagued by sustained
injuries, will have to work harder to maintain their places in the
rankings or move out of the way for others who play a greater
number of events and have higher rate of success in each.
</P>
<P>
"With next year's new ranking system, we will have to play more
tournaments," Seles said.
</P>
<P>
Following are the winners at Grand Slam tournaments:
</P>
<P>
Australian Open:
</P>
<P>
Men's singles winner: Boris Becker
</P>
<P>
Women's singles winner: Monica Seles
</P>
<P>
Wimbledon:
</P>
<P>
Men's singles winner: Richard Krajicek
</P>
<P>
Women's singles winner: Steffi Graf
</P>
<P>
French Open:
</P>
<P>
Men's singles winner: Yevbeny Kafelnikov
</P>
<P>
Women's singles winner: Steffi Graf
</P>
<P>
U.S. Open:
</P>
<P>
Men's singles winner: Pete Sampras
</P>
<P>
Women's singles winner: Steffi Graf
</P>
<P>
ATP Championships winner: Pete Sampras
</P>
<P>
WTA Chase Championships winner: Steffi Graf
</P>
