<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uygur Medicine Prospers in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- A traditional system of
medicine in China dating back 2,000 years has been given a major
tonic.
</P>
<P>
It will ensure that traditional Uygur medicine will continue to
enjoy the vigorous growth in West China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region that it has witnessed in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
And after passing stringent state-level tests some of the
ancient medicines have been given the go-ahead for mass production.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the local government and health departments,
25 hospitals have been built with 1,200 beds and more than 1,600
medical staff - all applying the unique form of medicine for
patients.
</P>
<P>
Three pilot factories for traditional Uygur medicine production
have been built in Hotan area and Kashi city. Training schools and
research institutes have also been set up to spread and develop
Uygur medicine.
</P>
<P>
Uygur medicine, one of the four major Chinese medicine systems
along with Chinese, Tibetan and Mongolian traditional medicines,
originated in Xinjiang in Qin Dynasty (221-206 B.C), and developed
into a complete medical system with local and ethnical
characteristics in Song Dynasty (960-1279).
</P>
<P>
According to the theory of Uygur medicine, nature is composed
of water, fire, earth and air. Birth, aging, ailment and death of
people were closely related to the four elements of the nature and
to the temperament, fluid, spirit and various forces in their
bodies.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the government of Xinjiang, aware of the fact
that it is the only region in China that keeps the use of Uygur
medicine, decided to take effective measures to develop it.
</P>
<P>
Academic circles of Uygur medicine run training courses,
including courses on orthopedics, dermatology and medicine
preparations, and clinical training centers have been established
to pass on the professional knowledge of the Uygur medicine to
younger generations.
</P>
<P>
The circles have published more than 20 books and magazines,
among which the Encyclopaedia of the Traditional Uygur Medicine
and the Diagnostics of the Traditional Uygur Medicine were
rewarded first and second prizes for Chinese Ethnical Publications.
</P>
<P>
At present, Uygur medicines, produced with modern preparation
equipment, have increased to more than 200 types, and 17 Uygur
medicines have passed the state appraisal of new medicines and can
be put into mass production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
