<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Emerging Opportunities for African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The past year also saw
western powers change their attitudes toward Africa. For example,
French President Jacques Chirac has come to visit African
countries three times since he was elected the head of state in
May, 1995.
</P>
<P>
Chirac's visits were to readjust French relations with African
countries, the French-speaking African countries in particular.
</P>
<P>
The United States also sent a trade mission headed by its then
Secretary of Commerce Ronald Brown to Cote d'Ivoire, Ghana, Kenya
and Uganda. Brown admitted that the United States had for long
neglected Africa and it was time for the U.S. to change and
scramble for the world's last undeveloped market in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, to show its confidence in Africa's
development, launched on March 15, 1996, a special initiative on
Africa, promising to grant it 25 billion U.S. Dollars over a span
of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. is mobilizing its organizations to help African
countries expand basic education and health care, improve water
and food security and increase the continent's competitiveness in
world trade.
</P>
<P>
The rich resources of rare metals and strategic materials in
Africa are getting more and more attractive in the world
community alongside progress of advanced science and technology.
</P>
<P>
At present, many of the precious materials needed by western
countries for its industries come from Africa. In addition, the
potential market in Africa is also drawing attention from the
outside.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the African Development Bank,
African countries's total value of foreign trade in 1995 was
210.21 billion U.S. Dollars, of which, 98.48 billion Dollars went
to export and 111.73 billion Dollars to import, registering an
increase of 11.86 percent and 13.56 percent respectively over
those of 1994.
</P>
<P>
Seizing the chances for development, a number of African
countries are now carrying out economic reforms by opening to the
outside world, and creating suitable environment to attract
investment and develop market-oriented economies. This means that
their economic future, on the whole, will be rosy as they are
heading for prosperity and development in the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
