<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Farmers Planting in Full Swing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December (Xinhua) -- Planting in Zimbabwe's commercial
farming sector is now in full swing and there are possibilities
of an above average harvest, Deputy Director of the Commercial
Farmers Union Richard Amyot said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Richard Amyot said that all the early planted crop is doing
well thanks to the rains that fell during the first two weeks of
this month.
</P>
<P>
he said 85 percent of the maize and 95 percent soyabeans had
been planted to date.
</P>
<P>
''planting is still going on and germination is pretty much
very good except a few areas whose soils are bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Amyot said the same hectares of maize will be planted this
year as last year while sorghum and soyabean have slightly
increased.
</P>
<P>
Cotton has seen a better start this season owing to more
surface water for irrigation, he added.
</P>
<P>
This year, Zimbabwe got a good harvest, registering a 49
percent increase in the agricultural sector and an eight percent
increase of the country's agro-based economy. 
</P>
