<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Holds Back Releasing of 216 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) held back releasing of 216 million U.S. Dollars in aid
to Kenya during the second phase of Kenya's Enhanced Structural
Adjustment Facility, the Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a report compiled by the London-based
Economist Intelligence Unit (EIU) as attributing the IMF's
holding back to Kenya's delays in carrying out reform pledges
promised in the Policy Framework paper (PFP).
</P>
<P>
The EIU report said that the Kenyan government "neither has
the skilled personnel nor the will to deliver on schedule the
many pledges made in the PFP."
</P>
<P>
The promise to split the Kenya Posts and Telecommunications
Corporation into three entities has not happened as promised by
the end of last October, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that while Kenya's economy is doing
reasonably well, economic growth is expected to slow down this
year due to weaker performances from agriculture and tourism.
</P>
<P>
It predicted that Kenya's GDP growth will fall from 4.9
percent in 1995 to 4.1 percent this year with a further fall to
3.9 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
While the manufacturing sector is constrained by an
over-strong currency of Shilling, the short-term outlook of the
tourism industry which is the main foreign exchange earner is
still not good, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cases of Violence Against Women, Children Go Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 24 (Xinhua) --South Africa has seen an
alarming increase in sexual violence against women and children
in the past one year.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper "the Citizen" on Tuesday quoted Safety and
Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi as saying that in the period
between January and August this year, 31,085 cases of rape or
attempted rape had been reported, an increase of 19 percent from
the same period in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Of the reported cases, about one third of the victims are
teenagers, while one in every six women was regularly abused by a
male partner.
</P>
<P>
While the violence agaisnt women is remarkably up, Mufamadi
said, tens of thousands of children have also become victimes of
criminals. He said the police has got 32,889 reports of crimes
against children from January to Novemenber this year, which
represented an increase of 24 percent of the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Referring to measures combating the crimes, Mufamadi said
departments of Welfare, Safety and Security, Justice and
Correctional Services had been mobilized over the festive season
which will allow victims easier access to police, welfare
severices and the courts.
</P>
<P>
The Festive season in South Africa usually starts from early
December and ends in mid-January.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi said police authorities were busy training police
officers to deal sensitively with victimes and the child
protection unit was on 24-hour standby. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
