<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 08:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu, Arafat to Conclude Hebron Deal Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu and Palestinian Authority (PA) President
Yasser Arafat are to hold a meeting today to conclude the
agreement on Israeli army's redeployment in Hebron, Israel Radio
reported this morning.
</P>
<P>
U.S. special Middle East coordinator Dennis Ross is also
expected to attend the session which is due to be held at 1100
a.m. local time (0900GMT) at the Erez checkpoint between Israel
and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials from both sides said that the leaders have
to iron out some last minute's details before signing the accord
on the redeployment in the West Bank town.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic breakthrough in the talks between Israel and
Palestine came Monday afternoon, when Netanyahu joined the
negotiations held at the King David Hotel in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mahmoud Abbas, Arafat's deputy and Palestinian top
negotiator, came from the Gaza Strip to participate in the
talks, which were a continuation of Sunday night's Marathon
talks in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Ross, who arrived here earlier this week to push
forward the Hebron talks, took an active role in the night-long
intensive negotiations, held at Arafat's Gaza Office.
</P>
<P>
Both Arafat and Ross expressed cautious optimism following
the talks, but Ross admitted that difference remained between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Ross then paid a sudden visit to Egypt Monday afternoon,
which later he said was designed to obtain Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak's blessing on what has been obtained by Israeli
and Palestinian negotiators.
</P>
<P>
On Monday night, following his talks with Netanyahu, Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy and Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, Ross continued on to Gaza where he met Arafat again
until early this morning.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the breakthrough is a package deal, Ross has
been working on, which includes Israel's commitment to further
redeploy its troops in the West Bank following the redeployment
in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Under the package deal, Israel also would agree to hold final
status talks on the West Bank and other issues after the
conclusion of the Hebron redeployment.
</P>
<P>
In light of the development, Ross will not be back to
Washington for Christmas as previously expected. He told
reporters that a lot of work has to be done. 
</P>
</TEXT>
