<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 08:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Cuts Bread Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has announced a cut of
nearly 10 percent in bread prices beginning in January 1997, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of Supply Muneer Suber made the announcement
Monday, according to English newspaper Jordan Times.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the announcement, a kilogram of high quality
bread will be sold at 200 fils (about 0.14 dollars) while bread
made of local flour will be offered at 170 fils (about 0.11
dollars) per kilogram, he said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has bought 150,000 tons of wheat at new global
market prices, he said.
</P>
<P>
In November, the Jordanian government made a decision to cut
bread prices by a narrow margin, but most of the bakeries did not
implement it because their bread was still made of the stored
flour purchased at a higher price.
</P>
<P>
In August, Jordan doubled the bread prices, which triggered
large-scale riots in the south of the kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
