<HEADLINE> Chinese Academy of Sciences to Aid Scientists in Western China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Academy of
Sciences (CAS) is to offer 10 million yuan (1.2 million
U.S. dollars) over the next few years to support science programs
launched by young scientists in western China.
</P>
<P>
Bai Chunli, Vice-President of the CAS, China's top scientific
research organ, said during the ninth Five-Year (1996-2000) Plan
period the academy is to fund 100 scientists below 40 years of age
in CAS branches in northwest China's Gansu Province, Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region, and southwest China's Yunnan Province for
their economy-oriented science programs.
</P>
<P>
Bai explained that the CAS will annually offer 20 young
scientists 100,000 yuan (12,000 dollars) each by the end of 2000
for research programs for local economic development.
</P>
<P>
He said the special fund will be used to foster young
scientists who lead research programs, and will remain in the
developing western areas.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jianfa, 34, deputy head of the CAS Lanzhou Geology
Institute, said that 66 percent of scientists in his institute are
under 45. In the past, many research projects for local economic
development could not be launched because of lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
Chen said with the special fund, young scientists will be able
to apply their knowledge in pushing forward development of western
areas where there are big gaps with the developed coastal areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
