<HEADLINE> China, Japan Sign Exchange of Notes on 1996 Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- China and Japan signed here
today an exchange of notes on the fourth batch of Japanese loan
in Japanese yen to China for the year 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the notes, the Japanese government is to provide a
loan totalled 170.511 billion yen to the Chinese government, on 22
projects covering the fields of transportation, energy,
environmental protection, agriculture, telecommunications and urban
infustructure, with a duration of 30 years (including a 10-year
grace) and a 2.3% annual interest rate for average projects, a
2.1% rate for environment projects.
</P>
<P>
Vice Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan and Japan's Ambassador to
China Yoshiyasu Sato signed the exchange of notes on behalf of
their respective governments.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, Japan has provided China with three
batches of loans in Japanese yen, amounting to 1,610 billion
yen. The loan, as a major part in Sino-Japanese trade and economic
cooperation, has helped China in its economic construction.
</P>
<P>
1996 is the first year to implement the fourth batch of loan
in the period of 1996 to 2000. Japan has promised in December 1994
to offer 580 billion yen for the first three years on 40 projects.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that An Min, assistant minister of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation, will sign an agreement on the 1996 loan
in Tokyo with head of Japan's Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund
this coming Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
