<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year of 1996 Worst Ever on Israel's Roads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 24 (Xinhua) -- There will have been some
24,830 traffic accidents by the end of the year, a 19.1 percent
increase over last year and the worst year ever, reported The
Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, quoting Elie Goldschmidt, chairman
of the Knesset (parliament) Economics Committee, as saying
Monday, the number of people injured in traffic accidents will
reach some 46,846, up 21.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
At that rate, Goldschmidt said, an astounding 600 out of
every 1,000 Israelis will be involved in a road accident
sometime in their lives, and one out of every 20 will be either
killed or seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
Experts have attributed the worsening traffic safety situation
to the rapid increase of vehicles and less roads. The late prime
minister, Yitzhak Rabin, said that Israel's infrastructure was
poor and at least 25 years behind the most developed European
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Transportation Ministry plans a number of new traffic
safety programs in 1997, ranging from road-safety courses for
elderly pedestrians to increased lighting on busy roads,
Transportation Minister Yitzhak Levy told the Knesset committee.
</P>
<P>
Levy said he intends to make road safety his ministry's top
priority. As a first step, he said, he plans to make the Road
Safety Administration and other units dealing with road safety
directly responsible to him.
</P>
<P>
Levy plans to set up an authority to coordinate a war on
traffic accidents -- one of the measures included in a road
safety bill that has been stalled in the Knesset due to Treasury
opposition.
</P>
<P>
This authority would include a research institute to serve
all ministries that deal with road safety, a unit to promote
public awareness of road safety, and a program to train civilian
drivers through the military authorities. Also planned are
better lighting for busy roads, electronic road signs that will
be easier to read, the testing of a new material to reduce
skidding on roads and the computerization of traffic tickets.
</P>
<P>
Goldschmidt said that traffic accidents result not only in
loss of life, but also in economic losses. Accidents cost the
economy about 1.2 billion shekels (some 400 million
U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Courts Achieve Marked Successes in Judicial Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- People's courts across China
have achieved overall progress in their judicial work this year, a
Chinese top judge said here today.
</P>
<P>
People's courts around the country accepted and handled
more than 4.69 million cases in criminal, civil, economic,
administrative and maritime fields from January to November this
year, a rise of 16.33 percent over last year, according to Ren
Jianxin, president of the Supreme People's Court.
</P>
<P>
Of these cases, more than 4.36 million were concluded, an
increase of 16 percent over the same period last year, Ren told
provincial Higher People's Courts presidents.
</P>
<P>
"Through their trials, the people's courts have made new
contributions to guaranteeing (China's) reform and opening-up and
promoting the smooth progress of socialist modernization drive,"
Ren said.
</P>
<P>
Since the central government made the strategic decision to
crackdown on crimes in April this year, the courts have mustered
their efforts to rein a number of criminals who pose serious
threats to the society, he said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of November, he added, the courts dealt with some
358,000 criminal cases in the harsh crackdown campaign, over 85
percent of which were concluded.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the courts stepped up the trials in other
fields. During the first 11 months this year, the courts handled
4.14 million cases concerning economic disputes, approximately 16
percent over last year. And the cases involved a total of 207.2
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
"The trials played an important role in safeguarding the
country's macro-economic control and maintaining economic order,
and promoting socialist ethical and cultural progress," Ren said.
</P>
<P>
From January 1, next year, the revised Criminal Procedure Law
will go into effect.
</P>
<P>
At present, the courts throughout the country are going in to
study and promote the Criminal Procedure Law, training judicial
officials and experimenting with the reform in court procedures so
as to gain fresh experience, Ren said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
