<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Books on Ethnic Groups Republished in Gansu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Gansu Province in northwest
China has collected and republished ancient books of various
ethnic groups to ensure that old cultures survive in the future.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, the province has compiled and published
52 books and translated four others, with another 26 edited and
due to come off the press soon.
</P>
<P>
Most of the books are written in Chinese and ethic minority
languages. Among them, those written in Tibetan language take up
the major part. Others feature Islamic and Mongolian cultures.
</P>
<P>
Some minor ethnic groups have no written records, so their
history and culture are preserved in ballads, epics, love songs
and folk tales.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the republished books are very helpful for
research on political, economic, cultural and religious affairs of
various ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with ancient records, new types of traditional
Chinese medicine have been developed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Chinese University Grads Set Up Ecological Farm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Five university graduates in
the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region have set up an
ecologically-sound farm in Miaoliuyin village in Dachengxi
Township.
</P>
<P>
The farm was established with a share-holding system in an
attempt to develop ecologically-friendly agriculture, when the
graduates went to the village last July.
</P>
<P>
More than 200,000 yuan (24,000 US dollars) was collected to set
up a chicken farm with 20,000 chickens, an edible fungus farm that
can produce 40,000 kg of fungi, and a fodder processing factory
with an annual production of 500 tons.
</P>
<P>
The grads have also held a variety of training classes to help
local farmers learn practical techniques.  
</P>
