<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhou Enlai, Deng Yingchao Memorial Hall to Be Built in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- A memorial hall of the late
Premier Zhou Enlai and his wife Deng Yingchao will be built in
north China's port city of Tianjin, according to a report in
today's "People's Daily".
</P>
<P>
A foundation stone laying ceremony was held here Monday, which
was attended by the municipal Party Secretary Gao Dezhan, the
Mayor Zhang Lichang, and more than 500 people from all walks of
life.
</P>
<P>
The memorial hall is scheduled to be completed and opened to
the public on March 5, 1998, Zhou's 100th birthday.
</P>
<P>
The hall will display life stories of the couple, who devoted
themselves to China's revolutionary cause and socialist
construction, and were esteemed by the Chinese people, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Zhou and Deng met and fell in love in Tianjin in the
1920s. They attended Nankai University where they entered upon
their revolutionary careers.
</P>
<P>
After the new China was established in 1949, the couple made
inspection trips to Tianjin for many times. They regarded the city
as their second hometown.
</P>
<P>
Before their deaths, Zhou and Deng respectively asked to spread
some of their ashes in the Haihe River running across
Tianjin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chi Haotian Back in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- General Chi Haotian,
vice-chairman of China's Central Military Commission, state
councillor and defense minister, returned to Beijing today after
concluding a visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Among those greeting Chi at the airport were General Fu
Quanyou, chief of the General Staff of the Chinese People's
Liberation Army; Yang Jingyu, deputy secretary-general of China's
State Council; Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister Li Zhaoxing; and
U.S. Ambassador to China Sasser James Ralph. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Ten World News Events in 1996 (Part One) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Following are the top ten
world news events in 1996 selected by the Xinhua News Agency:
</P>
<P>
1. First Asia-Europe Summit Establishes New Type of Asia-Europe
</P>
<P>
Relations
</P>
<P>
The first ever Asia-Europe Summit meeting brought together 26
heads of government -- 10 from Asia and 15 from the European Union
-- and President of the European Commission Jacques Santer on
March 1-2 in Bangkok, Thailand. To strengthen political dialogue
and promote economic cooperation between the two continents were
the major topics at the meeting. The meeting, under the theme
"Towards A New Asia-Europe Partnership for Greater Growth,"
adopted a chairman's statement, which would help establish a
fundamental framework for new type of Asia-Europe relations. The
meeting, as a fresh starting point for cooperation between the two
continents, would exert a positive influence on the set-up of the
international political and economic system.
</P>
<P>
2. U.S. Tougher Sanctions Against Cuba, Iran and Libya Incurs
</P>
<P>
Strong Condemnation from International Community
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate and the House of Representatives passed on
March 5 and 6 the Helms-Burton bill aiming to impose tougher
sanctions upon Cuba. The bill, sponsored by Senator Jesse Helms
and Representative Dan Burton, claims to punish foreign companies
and individuals doing business with Cuba. In July, the Senate and
House passed the Iran-Libya Sanctions Act, claiming to apply
sanctions against companies with more than 40 million U.S. dollars
of investment in the two countries. The U.S. power politics and
hegemonism incurred condemnation from other countries, including
some U.S. allies.
</P>
<P>
3. China, Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan Sign
</P>
<P>
Border Agreement
</P>
<P>
The Presidents of China, Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and
Tajikistan signed an agreement on confidence-building in the
military field in border areas on April 26 in Shanghai,
China. Under the agreement, the military forces of both sides
stationed along border areas would neither attack each other nor
conduct military exercises aimed at each other. The agreement also
specified that limits should be imposed on the scale, scope and
number of military exercises, and the concerned sides should
inform each other of any major military activities taking place in
any area within 100 kilometers of the borderline. The
multi-lateral political and military agreement has exerted deep
and far-reaching impact on maintaining peace, stability and
development in the Asia-Pacific region and the whole world as
well. On April 25, one day before the signing of the agreement,
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and his Russian counterpart, Boris
Yeltsin, met in Beijing and discussed the establishment of an
equal strategic partnership between the two countries to face
challenges of the coming 21st century.
</P>
<P>
4. Likud Leader Netanyahu Defeats Peres to Become New Israeli
</P>
<P>
PM; Middle East Peace Process Stalled
</P>
<P>
On May 31, Likud challenger Benjamin Netanyahu defeated Shimon
Peres and became the new Israeli prime minister. Netanyahu and his
cabinet pursued a hard line policy and refused to make any
concessions on security issues. Incessant bloodshed was triggered
by Israel's lifting a ban on Jewish settlement expansion in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip, and opening an underground tunnel in
east Jerusalem, which Muslims accused of being a plot to undermine
their holy places above, the Al-Aqsa mosque. The Middle East peace
process was thus stalled.
</P>
<P>
5. Japanese PM Visits Yasukuni Shrine; Japan's Political
</P>
<P>
Orientation Tilts Toward Rightism
</P>
<P>
On July 29, Ryutaro Hashimoto became the first Japanese prime
minister since 1985 to visit the Tokyo-based Yasukuni Shrine
housing tablets of 14 class-A war criminals. In addition, Japanese
rightists kept provoking conflicts on China's Diaoyu Islands; the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) requested visiting foreign
heads of state and other political figures to visit the Yasukuni
Shrine; LDP parliament members made repeated efforts in
whitewashing Japan's history of invasion; and Japan and the
U.S. agreed to expand their security accord to cover the entire
Asia-Pacific region. Japan's political orientation has aroused
great concern and vigilance from neighboring Asian countries and
the whole international community as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Ten World News Events in 1996 (Part Two) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
6. Fightings in Eastern Zaire Drive Millions of Refugees Fleeing
</P>
<P>
Since early September, fierce fightings in eastern Zaire
between Zairean troops and the anti-government ethnic Tutsi people
as well as the neighboring Rwandan and Burundi troops have forced
millions of refugees, mainly from Rwanda and Burundi, to flee. In
mid-November, the U.N. Security Council passed a resolution to
send multinational troops to eastern Zaire. With the help of the
international community, hundreds of thousands of refugees have
returned home.
</P>
<P>
7. U.N. General Assembly Approves Nuclear Test Ban Treaty
</P>
<P>
The U.N. General Assembly approved on September 10 the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT). Under the CTBT, all
signatory countries would be banned from conducting any nuclear
tests, and committed not to trigger, encourage or participate in
any nuclear tests. On September 24, the U.N. arranged open
signature for the CTBT, and China, France, Russia, Britain and the
U.S. were among the first signatories. So for, the treaty has
collected more than 130 signatory countries. It is an important
step forward the international community took to a final
elimination of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
8. Air Disasters Occur Frequently; Air Traffic Security to Be
</P>
<P>
Strengthened
</P>
<P>
On November 12, 349 passengers were killed when a Saudi Airway
Boeing 747 and a Kazakh Il-76 cargo plane collided in mid-air over
Haryana State, India, becoming the worst air collision in human
history. On July 17, a U.S. TWA (Trans World Airlines) 747 jet
with 230 aboard exploded in mid-air shortly after its takeoff from
New York JFK airport. No survivors have been found. Air accidents
occurred frequently in the world this year, which were attributed
to the fact that safety control technologies lag behind a rapidly
developing air transport industry.
</P>
<P>
9. U.S. Vetos Reelection of Boutros Boutros-Ghali; Kofi Annan
</P>
<P>
Elected New U.N. Secretary-General
</P>
<P>
After the November 19 veto by the U.S. of
U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali's reelection bid for
a second term, the Security Council recommended on December 13 to
the General Assembly Kofi Annan of Ghana as a new candidate. On
December 17, the Assembly appointed Annan Secretary-General of the
United Nations for a term of office beginning on January 1, 1997
and ending on December 31, 2001.
</P>
<P>
10. APEC Leaders Gather in Philippines Where Chinese and
</P>
<P>
 U.S. presidents meet
</P>
<P>
The fourth informal leadership meeting of the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation forum (APEC) was held on November 25 in
Subic, the Philippines. The meeting adopted a Manila Action Plan,
and passed a guideline document on closer economic and technical
cooperation among APEC members. On November 24, Chinese President
Jiang Zemin met his U.S. counterpart, Bill Clinton, in Manila,
which was seen as of great significance in improving and
developing Sino-U.S. relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Progress in Xinjiang's Oil Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- A total of 40 oil and gas
fields have been so far discovered in Tarim, Junggar and
Turpan-Hami, the three major basins in the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region in northwest China, according to the China
National Petroleum Corp (CNPC).
</P>
<P>
These oil and gas fields have a combined annual crude
production capacity of more than 15 million tons, CNPC said.
</P>
<P>
The three basins have an aggregate proven oil and gas reserves
equivalent to 2 billion tons of crude oil.
</P>
<P>
A total of 26 oil and gas bearing structures of industrial
development value have been discovered in nine oil and gas fields
in Tarim, and oil-rich strata have been discovered in 13 of the 23
key oil wells which have been sunk in the Tarim Basin.
</P>
<P>
A proven reserves of more than 50 million tons of oil was added
in the Turpan-Hami Basin this year. And in the Junggar Oil Field,
the Xiaoguai field with a proven reserve of 59 million tons of oil
has been put into operation.
</P>
<P>
The official said that with these successes, the verified oil
and gas reserves in the three major basins will hit 1.5 billion
tons by the year 2000 and their combined annual oil output will
then reach 24 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coordinator: Israeli-Palestinian Summit May Not </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. special Middle East
coordinator Dennis Ross said today that he did not expect
differences between Israel and the Palestinians over Hebron
would be solved through one meeting, Israel Army Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Ross made the remarks before a summit meeting between
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat at the Erez checkpoint between
Israel and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was planned to start at 1100 a.m. (0900 GMT)
as previously announced by the two sides, did not begin at this
hour, according to the Army Radio report.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who is also expected to attend the meeting aimed at
making a final push to conclude an agreement on Israeli army's
redeployment in Hebron, said today's summit meeting was a
beginning of long process of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that Ross' remarks indicated that
Netanyahu and Arafat may hold follow-up meetings, before they
could finally close the accord on the Hebron redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, senior officials from both sides said that
the leaders have to iron out some last minute's details
before signing the accord.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic breakthrough in the talks between Israel and
the Palestinians came Monday afternoon, when Netanyahu joined
the negotiations held at the King David Hotel in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mahmoud Abbas, Arafat's deputy and top Palestinian
negotiator, came from the Gaza Strip to participate in the
talks, which were a continuation of Sunday night's Marathon
talks in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Ross, who arrived here earlier this week to
push forward the Hebron talks, took an active role in the
night-long intensive negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Both Arafat and Ross expressed cautious optimism following
the talks, but Ross admitted that difference remained between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Ross then paid a sudden visit to Egypt Monday afternoon to
obtain Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's support for what has
been achieved by Israeli and Palestinian negotiators.
</P>
<P>
On Monday night, following his talks with Netanyahu, Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy and Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai as well as Ross went to Gaza to meet Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The cause behind the previously-made breakthrough is a package
deal Ross has been working on, which includes Israel's commitment
to further redeploy its troops in the West Bank following the
redeployment in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Under the package deal, Israel would also agree to hold
final status talks on the West Bank and other issues a few
weeks after the conclusion of the Hebron redeployment.
</P>
<P>
In light of the development, Ross will not be back to
Washington for Christmas as previously expected, and he told
reporters that a lot of work had to be done. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Famine Looms in Kenya's Lake Victoria Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Economic activity and food
production in Kenya's Lake Victoria Region are now threatened by
the rapidly-spreading water hyacinth in the Lake Victoria, said a
report compiled by the Kenyan Ministry of Environment and Natural
Resources.
</P>
<P>
Fish production is expected to fall by a big margin this
season and further in future if the weed is not controlled, the
report noted.
</P>
<P>
The report paints a bleak future for the fishing industry of
Nyanza Province along the lake which accounts for more than 50
percent of the fish consumed locally and exported.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of fishermen and middlemen who earned a living from
fishing related activities, are now rendered jobless.
</P>
<P>
Crop growing is alien to the communities living along the lake
as they have always depended on fishing as a source of money and
food.
</P>
<P>
A 65-year-old fisherman, Thomas Ogweno was quoted as saying:
"Once we stop fishing, there is no alternative. Our farms are
barren and we have to sell fish to buy maize meals and other
foodstuffs. No fish no food."
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government is concerned about the fast-growing weed
which had almost blocked the lake and committed to eradicating
the water hyacinth from the lake through biological methods.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has agreed to provide 70 million U.S. Dollars
to the three East African countries of Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda
to help fight the water hyacinth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Courts in China to Continue Cracking down on Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- People's courts in China shall
continue to carry on the national crackdown on crimes next year in
a bid to safeguard social stability, Ren Jianxin, president of the
Supreme People's Court, said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The unified and intensified campaign on cracking down crimes
this year has beat down the arrogance of criminals, reversing poor
public security in some places," Ren told the presidents of
provincial Higher People's Courts.
</P>
<P>
"It is a long-term strategic task of the people's courts to
carry forward forceful crackdown on crimes that jeopardize public
security and undermine economy, and to go all out to safeguard
social stability with utmost efforts," Ren said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the courts to continue combating violent, gun-related
and organized crimes, pornography, gambling, and narcotics-related
crimes, prostitution, kidnaping of women, illegal publication,
which are all social evils.
</P>
<P>
The courts should carry on their powerful fight against various
violent and group crimes and vicious gangs of hooligans. Chief
criminals who are merciless and pose great harms to society must
be brought to justice according to law.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the courts should continue to deal serious blows
at embezzlement, bribery and other crimes disrupting economic
order, in order to ensure the sound development of market economy.
</P>
<P>
Such crimes are still serious in some places, and major cases
have occurred time and again, and the sum of money related to
the cases tends to grow.
</P>
<P>
As a result, he noted, the people's courts at all levels should
focus their emphasis on law-breakers in the country's Party and
government institutions and administrative departments in charge
of economic activities.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the courts should step up crackdown on financial
fraud, smuggling, swindling, tax evasion, and making counterfeit
goods, Ren said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Returnees Benefit From RAP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 24 (Xinhua) - A total of 34,400 Vietnam's boat
people who returned from regional camps have benefited from a
professional training project under the Returnee Assistance
Program (RAP), according to the Ministry of Labor, War Invalids
and Social Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Those people have been trained at 12 job training centers on a
pilot scheme throughout the country which has selected 56
employment service centers and factories to either provide job
training or generate employment for returnees.
</P>
<P>
The three-year RAP, which has been operating since June 1996,
is aimed at assisting the reintegration of boat people who
returned to the country from camps in Hong Kong and Southeast
Asian countries since July 1, 1994.
</P>
<P>
The program consists of credit, job training, social
assistance, and small infrastructure development projects, the
ministry added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Telephone Capacity to Top 100 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- China's telephone capacity is
expected to top 100 million by the end of this year, pushing the
telephone penetration rate to 6,2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Chunjiang, a spokesman for the Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications, said today that in 1995 the two figures were
80 million and 4.66 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the first year of China's Ninth Five-Year Plan period
(1996--2000), China achieved a 34.5 percent increase in business
volume for posts and telecommunications service. The telephone
penetration rate in urban areas, Zhang said, has jumped from 17
percent in 1995 to 22 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Besides, China's mobile telecommunications service is now
nationwide and the global system for mobile communications (GSM)
business has extended to 261 prefectures or cities, covering over
1,000 counties, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, China has invested 98 billion yuan in the posts and
telecommunications projects which included long-distance optical
fibre networks such as Beijing-Taiyuan-Xi'an, Wuhan-Chongqing,
Jinan-Qingdao and Nanjing-Hangzhou. A total of 31 ground satellite
 stations have been built or upgraded.
</P>
<P>
According to China's Ninth Five-Year Plan, China's telephone
capacity is expected to reach 170 million by the turn of the
century, up by 20 million each year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
