<HEADLINE> S. Korean Prosecutors Demand Life in Jail for U.S. Soldier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 24 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's Seoul District
Public Prosecutor's Office (SDPPO) demanded life in jail for an
American soldier on murder charge here today.
</P>
<P>
Eric Munnich Stephen, serviceman of the second division of the
Eighth United States Army, was charged with killing a South Korean
woman, Lee Ki-soon, near a U.S. military base in Tongduchon, South
Korea's Kyonggi Province, on September 7 this year.
</P>
<P>
"Although the accused committed the crime while intoxicated, it
is requested that he be severely punished in view of the
horrendous nature of his offense, which was stabbing the victim's
throat several times with a deadly weapon," said SDPPO Prosecutor
Choi Kyo-il.
</P>
<P>
Stephen, 22, has admitted to prosecutors that he stabbed Lee, a
prostitute, to death in a brothel in Tongduchon.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. soldier has been detained at a U.S. military camp in
Kyonggi Province after he killed the South Korean woman.
</P>
<P>
On October 11, the South Korean prosecution requested the
transfer of the custody of the American serviceman before a
verdict is given, but the U.S. military authorities refused.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 years, some 40 murders have been linked to the
U.S. military presence in South Korea, where 37,000 American
troops are stationed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
