<HEADLINE> &AMP;0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Angered by sharp fall in stock
prices in the last few days, Dhaka's kerb market traders have
threatened to begin an indefinite sit-in from December 29, Dhaka
Stock Exchange (DSE) sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The kerb market traders also demanded the resignation of
Finance Minister S.A. Kibria, who was accused of making discursive
statements on the capital market, stock sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The DSE, center of all agitation, again witnessed a heavy sell
pressure Monday, pulling down the benchmark price index for the
fifth consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
The all shares price index of the country's premier bourse
plummeted by 82,28 points to 2375.38 points in Monday's brief
trading. Just a month ago, the index once climbed up to more than
3,500 points.
</P>
<P>
"If the situation continues, the index will go below the 2,000
point mark by this week," said a DSE official. "And the crash mark
of 1,500 points, set by the finance minister, is not far off."
</P>
<P>
The kerb market traders, who had successfully sieged the DSE
building for a few days earlier this month in the wake of
continued fall of shares prices, blamed manipulation by a section
of the DSE members and urged the government to normalize the stock
market as soon as possible.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
