<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Islamic Relics Discovered In East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, December 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 20 carved Islamic
tombstones from the Northern Song Dynasty (960-1127) have been
unearthed in Quanzhou, a port city in east China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists say that the stones were discovered on Tumen
Street, the city's oldest.
</P>
<P>
The gravestones are engraved with cloud and flower patterns,
one archeologist says, and their carvings and shapes indicate that
Arab traders had residences and cemeteries on the street about
1,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The discovery has also shown that Quanzhou was a prosperous
trade and religious center that attracted Chinese and other
businessmen and religious believers in ancient times.
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists said that the relics will be valuable for
research on Islamic practices in Quanzhou long ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
