<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Roundup: Israelis, Palestinians Try to Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority President
Yasser Arafat are holding a summit meeting at present in an effort
to conclude an agreement on the Israeli army's redeployment in the
West Bank of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
There is cautious optimism, with doubts still lingering. Before
the meeting started, U.S. Middle East special coordinator Dennis
Ross said that he did not expect differences between Israel and
the Palestinians over Hebron would be solved through one meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was scheduled to start at 1100 a.m.
(0900 GMT) at the Erez checkpoint between Israel and the Gaza
Strip, was postponed for almost an hour and started with a
one-to-one meeting between Netanyahu and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who is also expected to join the meeting later together
with other senior Israeli and Palestinian officials, said today's
summit meeting was a beginning of long process of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Israeli media pointed out that Ross's remarks indicated that
Netanyahu and Arafat may hold follow-up meetings, before they
could finally close the accord on the Hebron redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, senior officials from both sides said that
the leaders have to iron out some last minute's details
before signing the accord.
</P>
<P>
According to the Oslo accords, Israeli army was originally
supposed to have completed its redeployment in the Hebron area by
March 28, a pull-back from approximately 80 percent of the town.
</P>
<P>
However, following a series of suicide bombing attacks in
Israel in February and March which killed 60 people and wounded
more than 100 others, former Prime Minister Shimon Peres delayed
the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Last May, the previous Israeli government announced that
the army's withdrawal from Hebron would be carried out after
the May 29 general elections, due to security reasons.
</P>
<P>
However, Peres, who was defeated by Likud Party Chairman
Netanyahu in the elections, said afterwards that he would leave
the decision of the redeployment to the new prime minister and
his government.
</P>
<P>
Hebron, some 30 kilometers south of Jerusalem, is a place of
pilgrimage for Christians, Jews and Moslems alike. Tradition has
it that patriarchs Abraham, Isaac, Jacob and their wives are all
buried in the Machpelah Cave (Haram al-Khalil).
</P>
<P>
There are some 450 Jewish settlers now living in the
center of Hebron, who moved back to the city's old Jewish
neighborhood after the 1967 War, during which Israel took over
the town from the Jordanian authority.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there are some 200,000 Palestinians living in most
other parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
During his election campaign, Netanyahu said that he would like
Hebron to be part of the final status arrangements with the
Palestinians, but, at the same time, he also said he would stand
by the international agreements.
</P>
<P>
In October, Israel and the Palestinians started a new round
of continuous talks on the redeployment in Hebron, which had
already been delayed for more than half a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
