<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Roundup: Israelis, Palestinians Try to Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the talks, Israel insisted on changes in the security
arrangements agreed to under the Oslo accords, in light of
the violent confrontation between Israelis and Palestinians in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip in September.
</P>
<P>
During the confrontations, triggered by the opening of
the Hasmonean Tunnel by Israel in Jerusalem's Old City, more
than 70 people were killed and hundreds of others wounded.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the confrontations, which had included
exchanges of fire between Israeli troops and the Palestinian
police, U.S. President Bill Clinton called for an emergency
summit in Washington to resuscitate the peace process.
</P>
<P>
As one of the few results of the summit, Israel and the
Palestinians agreed to hold round-the-clock talks in a bid to
resolve their differences.
</P>
<P>
However, after four weeks of continuous talks, with the
participation of Ross and other U.S. officials, Israel and the
Palestinians failed to complete a deal.
</P>
<P>
In November, Israel and Palestinians had once again tried to
close the Hebron deal through U.S. mediations, but again failed to
work out an agreement on the security arrangements and other
related issues.
</P>
<P>
Israeli media then reported that the main stumbling blocks
continued to be the right of "hot pursuit of terrorists" into the
Palestinian self-ruled areas, which was required by Israel, and
kinds of weapons to be used by Palestinian policemen in Hebron
after the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The latest dramatic breakthrough in the talks between Israel
and the Palestinians came Monday afternoon, when Netanyahu
joined the negotiations held at the King David Hotel in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mahmoud Abbas, Arafat's deputy and top Palestinian
negotiator, came from the Gaza Strip to participate in the
talks, which were the continuation of Sunday night's Marathon
talks in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who arrived here earlier this week to push forward the
Hebron talks, took an active role in the night-long intensive
negotiations held at Arafat's Gaza Office.
</P>
<P>
Both Arafat and Ross expressed cautious optimism following the
talks, but Ross admitted that difference still remained between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Ross then paid a sudden visit to Egypt Monday afternoon,
which later he said was designed to obtain Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak's blessing on what has been achieved by Israeli
and Palestinian negotiators.
</P>
<P>
On Monday night, following their consultation with Netanyahu,
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy and Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, along with Ross, went to Gaza where they met Arafat
again until early this morning.
</P>
<P>
The cause behind the long-hoped breakthrough is a package
deal that Ross has been working on, which includes Israel's
commitment to further redeploy its troops in the West Bank
following the redeployment in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Under the package deal, Israel also would agree to hold
final status talks on the West Bank and other issues a few
weeks after the conclusion of the Hebron redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli relations are the core of the Middle
East conflict, without a solution to which there will be no real
peace in the Middle East. A long way still lies ahead concerning
the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations on many issues such as the
final status of the West Bank and Jerusalem, even if the Hebron
issue is completely solved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
