<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Trade Deficit to Surpass 20 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 24 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's trade deficit this
year is expected to exceed 20 billion U.S. dollars, higher than
the government's projection of 18 billion dollars, the Ministry of
International Trade and Industry said here today.
</P>
<P>
During the first 11 months of this year, South Korea had a
trade deficit of 19.01 billion dollars, with exports reaching
117.62 billion dollars, up 3.8 percent from the same period last
year. Imports grew by 10.8 percent to 136.63 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The export of petrochemical products declined by 1.9 percent to
84.01 billion dollars and semiconductors by 17.7 percent to 16.39
billion.
</P>
<P>
The import of raw materials surged by 9.8 percent to 67.6
billion dollars, capital goods by 9.6 percent to 53.81 billion
dollars and consumer products by 20.5 percent to 15.2 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports to industrialized nations slipped by 7.4 percent to
52.38 billion dollars, while those to developing countries went up
by 15 percent to 65.24 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports from developed nations surged by 7.3 percent to 89.84
billion dollars and those from developing countries soared by 18.1
percent to 46.79 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, South Korea's trade deficit stood at 10.06 billion
dollars, up 58.7 percent from 6.34 billion dollars registered in
1994.
</P>
<P>
Exports increased by 30.3 percent from 1994 to 125.06 billion
dollars in 1995, the fastest yearly growth since 1987, when a
36.2-percent gain was recorded.
</P>
<P>
Imports increased faster at a rate of 32 percent to 135.12
billion dollars, the highest since a 35.8 percent growth in 1979.
</P>
</TEXT>
