<HEADLINE> NPC Law Committee Vice-Chairman on Draft Law on Stationing Troops in HK SAR (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese official said today
that the draft law on the stationing of troops in the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) conforms to the country's
Constitution and the Basic Law, reflecting the "one country, two
systems" principle.
</P>
<P>
Wang Shuwen, vice-chairman of the Law Committee of China's
National People's Congress (NPC), was reporting in Beijing on the
result of an examination of the draft law at the 23rd Session of
the Eighth NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
He said that the last Session of the Eighth NPC Standing
Committee had made a preliminary examination of the draft, and the
NPC Law Committee also held two meetings on December 3 and 18 to
deliberate on opinions put forward by NPC Standing Committee
members, as well as by some relevant departments, experts and
people in Hong Kong,
</P>
<P>
Law Committee members held that it is necessary to formulate
the law on the stationing of troops in the Hong Kong SAR, in order
to ensure that the troops, sent by the central people's government
to Hong Kong for defence purpose, will fulfill their obligations
according to the law, he said.
</P>
<P>
This move is also to aim at safeguarding state sovereignty,
national unity and territorial integrity, as well as Hong Kong's
security, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the committee made suggestions on revisions to the
draft, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
