<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Draft Law on Exclusive Economic Zone and Continental Shelf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- China today unveiled details
of a new draft law covering its Exclusive Economic Zones (EEZ) and
Continental Shelf.
</P>
<P>
The law was submitted today to the 23rd session of the Standing
Committee of the 8th National People's Congress (NPC), China's
highest legislative body, for examination and deliberation.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng said in the motion submitted to the
committee that the draft law was aimed to guarantee the exercise
of China's sovereignty and jurisdiction over its EEZs and
continental shelf, and safeguard its maritime rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhaoxing, vice-foreign minister, explained the draft at the
meeting, saying the law, which does not go beyond the contents of
the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea, has been made
in a bid to ensure the implementation of the convention in China.
</P>
<P>
The draft stipulates that China's EEZs are maritime areas
within 200 nautical miles, beginning from boundary line of
territorial waters, which is in full accordance with the
international convention.
</P>
<P>
The draft provides that overlap claims on EEZs and continental
shelves between China and other countries with bordering coasts,
or those standing opposite to China geographically, are to be
settled according to international law in the spirit of fairness.
</P>
<P>
The draft also makes specific stipulations about China's
sovereignty and jurisdiction upon its EEZs and continental shelf
and the country's legitimate rights to explore, exploit and manage
natural resources in such activities as fisheries and minerals
within its EEZs and continental shelf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
