<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Make Large-Range Amendments to Criminal Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Draft amendments to China's
Criminal Law were sent today to the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), the country's highest
legislative body, for examination and deliberation.
</P>
<P>
Wang Hanbin, Vice Chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, gave
an explanation of the amendments at the ongoing 23rd session of
the eighth NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
He said the amendments will adopt more definite and concrete
articles on the basic principles of the country's Criminal Law
that has been practiced for 17 years. He added that China is
striving for the making of "a unified and relatively complete
criminal code."
</P>
<P>
According to the draft amendments, "counter-revolutionary
offences" will be replaced by "jeopardizing state security
offences".
</P>
<P>
Wang explained that the amendment is being made to improve the
criminal law system, concerning the state system, and safeguarding
the overall interest of the country.
</P>
<P>
As for capital punishments stipulated by the Criminal Law, he
said, China will neither increase nor reduce articles on crimes
that carry death sentences.
</P>
<P>
Wang stressed that the amendments to the Criminal Law are
another important step forward in the improvement of the country's
criminal judicial system, after adoption of the amendments to the
Criminal Procedure Law in March this year.
</P>
<P>
Another important amendment suggested is that if an act is not
specifically covered by articles of the Criminal Law, it cannot
lead to a criminal conviction. According to the current law,
people can be convicted of a crime according to articles on a
similar crime.
</P>
<P>
The draft amendments also include stricter rules on deduction
of penalties and release on parole in an effort to prevent
criminals from further endangering society, and their protection
offered by corrupt officials.
</P>
<P>
According to the amendments, punishments not covered by the
criminal law will need to be approved by the the Trial Committee
of the Supreme People's Court instead of by the trial committees
of local courts.
</P>
<P>
The amendments also widened the range of legitimate defenses,
to encourage the voluntary acts in security. Policemen acting in
the line of duty will have no criminal responsibility after
causing injury or death with their arms, the amendments suggested.
</P>
<P>
Those who surrender themselves to the police, or admit to other
crimes after their arrest will receive lower sentences.
</P>
<P>
The amendments also give a new list of crimes, including
organized crime, computer crime and abnormal security market acts.
</P>
<P>
The existing Criminal Law has 192 articles and 22 supplementary
regulations and the amended law will have 384 articles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
