<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Draft Law on Blood Donation Submitted for Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- China is to introduce a new
law to make illegal dealings in blood illegal. The law aims to
encourage more people to become voluntary blood donors to meet a
growing demand for blood and blood products.
</P>
<P>
A draft bill on the donation of blood has been submitted to the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC),
China's highest legislative body, for examination and discussion.
</P>
<P>
Public Health Minister Chen Minzhang explained the draft law to
the 23rd Session of the Eighth Standing Committee of the NPC,
which was held today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The law provides that every healthy Chinese citizen aged 18 to
55 has a duty to donate blood. Staff workers at government organs,
college and university students, and armymen are asked to play a
leading role in blood donation.
</P>
<P>
The draft law also stipulates that citizens have the right to
use blood freely. It encourages individuals, families and work
units to "deposit" blood for possible personal use.
</P>
<P>
In order to prevent blood donation stations and medical
agencies from seeking exorbitant profits, the draft law prohibits
them from selling blood to blood product companies.
</P>
<P>
The law also formulates strict measures to guarantee the health
of blood donors and recipients of blood and blood products.
</P>
<P>
Minister Chen said the draft law on blood donating will help
satisfy increasing demands for blood, and halt illegal dealings in
blood, safeguarding the health of people.
</P>
<P>
The demand for blood in Chinese hospitals reached 800 tons last
year, with transfusions given to more than four million
people. And the demand is increasing at a rate of seven to ten
percent annually, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
However, paid blood donating dominated the method of blood
supply at present. Chen blamed paid blood donations and illegal
blood banks for contributing to poor quality of blood, and the
spread of diseases transmitted through transfused blood.
</P>
<P>
"It is an urgent task to formulate the law to improve the
backward conditions of blood donations in China," he said.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 10 provincial and 11 city legislative bodies or
governments have issued local regulations on blood donations. The
Ministry of Public Health has published a series of rules to
regulate the work since 1990.
</P>
<P>
So far, 253 blood donation stations responsible for blood
collection, storage and transportation have been set up across the
country. 
</P>
