<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Maps Out Plan for 1997 Personnel Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- China will continue the reform
of its personnel system in 1997, giving priority to the civil
service system, personnel reform in social institutions, and the
comprehensive development of human resources.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a national conference of senior personnel officials,
minister of Personnel Song Defu said here today that personnel
work in 1997 should conform to reforms of the agricultural sector
and state enterprises, to better serve the country's economic
construction.
</P>
<P>
In a letter of congratulation to the conference, Chinese
Premier Li Peng praised the achievements of personnel work in
1996. He expressed the hope that personnel departments can make
greater contributions to China's reform, opening up, and
modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
"Personnel departments should further deepen internal reforms,
improve the civil service system, and strengthen the development
of human resources next year," the premier noted.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Song said that major tasks for personnel
departments across the country in 1997 should include spread of
the civil service system at county and township levels, and
introduction of a competitive mechanism into the employment system
of both the government and social institutions.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, we should conduct general predictions and planning
for the development of human resources, and carry out reforms of
the social security system, especially reform of pension
insurance," he added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the reform of personnel systems is to some
extent "a readjustment of interests", which is inevitably
complicated and sensitive.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, we should make progress in a safe and steady way,"
he asserted, adding that interests of various social groups, such
as civil servants, professionals and technicians, managers,
ordinary employees, and retired officials, must be taken into
account.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Party's control over officials, which he
described as the "root" of personnel work, must be maintained,
though the way of management could be improved.
</P>
<P>
"We should also strictly prevent the application of commercial
rules in personnel work, and resolutely object to any practice
of 'trading power for money'," he added.
</P>
<P>
Claiming major successes for personnel work in 1996, Song said
the number of provinces that adopted open exams in the recruiting
of new civil servants has surged from 10 to 25, while over 1,800
labor markets for skilled personnel have been established across
the country.
</P>
<P>
"The overall number of government employees is on the decline,
showing the effects of state streamlining efforts," he claimed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
