<HEADLINE> China to Rename Counterrevolutionary Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- A draft amendment to China's
Criminal Law for the renaming of the Counter Revolutionary Crime
as jeopardizing state security crime, was today submitted to the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
The proposed change will undergo examination and deliberation.
</P>
<P>
Wang Hanbin, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
NPC, explained the draft amendment to the committee, China's
highest legislative body, saying that the suggestion was made in
consideration of changed circumstances, and the overall interests
of the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that the stipulation about the counter-revolutionary
crime included in the Criminal law has played an important role in
safeguarding state security and socialist system and the
consolidation of the people's democratic dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
However, political, economic and social development in recent
years has given birth to a series of new problems, Wand noted.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft, counter-revoluntary activities
stipulated in the current Criminal Law are still all considered as
crime, with the exception that some of the activities will be
dealt as ordinary criminal acts.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
