<HEADLINE> '96 China's Top Ten Science Events </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- A new strain of rice,
developed by scientists in China, today topped the list of the
country's top ten scientific events of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The list of China's Top Ten Science Events was published today
in Beijing, citing research and development of double-hybrid rice
strains in first place.
</P>
<P>
The selection, organized by Chinese Academy of Sciences, the
Chinese Academy of Engineering and China Science News, attracted
408 academicians from the two prestige academies.
</P>
<P>
The following are the other science events in the list:
</P>
<P>
--The Institute of Modern Physics has for the first time in the
world synthesized the new nuclear Am-235.
</P>
<P>
--The National Conference on Science Popularization has been
held for the first time since the founding of New China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
--National Environmental Protection Agency decided that 15
kinds of small factories that cause heavy pollution should be
closed across the nation before September 30.
</P>
<P>
--A hundred academicians from two academies who gave public
lectures in ten cities in China, including Beijing, Shanghai and
Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
--A large current proton cyclotron was developed at the Chinese
Institute of Nuclear Research.
</P>
<P>
--Great achievements have been scored over the ten-year period
after the implementation of the "863" High-Technology Program,
which is a medium and long-term plan for the development of
China's high technology, and the Spark Program which is aimed at
providing township enterprises with widely applicable techniques.
</P>
<P>
--Five state scientific bodies called on scientists and
technicians to promote socialist ethical and cultural progress.
</P>
<P>
--A national leading group for China's science and technology
was set up, which is headed by Chinese Premier Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
--China's first law governing the application of scientific and
technological achievements went into effect on October 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
