<HEADLINE> Thailand Sets Macro-Economic Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Finance Ministry
today officially announced the country's key macro-economic
targets for the next two or three years, setting the annual
economic growth rate at 7.0 to 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release from the government house today,
Thailand will try to achieve an annual growth rate of 7 to 10
percent in its exports during the next two or three years.
</P>
<P>
The country's inflation rate will be curbed at 5 percent in
1997 and then will be brought down below the level in the
following years.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit will be kept at around 7.5 to 7.9
percent of the country's gross domestic product in 1997 and then
will be further reduced in the following one or two years.
</P>
<P>
The targets set by Thailand's new government led by Prime
Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh for the upcoming years are
generally lower than those set by the previous government led by
Banharn Silpa-Archa after the country suffered an economic
slowdown over the past year.
</P>
<P>
The Banharn government earlier set an 8.5 percent economic
growth and an 18 percent export growth this year, but the year is
ending with the country expected to see only a 7 percent economic
growth and a near-zero growth in its exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
