<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: A Non-End Chess Game in South Lebanon (Part 1) (by Shao Jie) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 24 (Xinhua) -- In the year 1996, Lebanon and
Israel have failed again to go beyond a circle in which they
accuse each other of making trouble in south Lebanon in the wake
of every single violent incident, especially when casualties were
caused.
</P>
<P>
An Asian diplomat in Beirut described south Lebanon, the last
active battlefront of the Arab-Israeli conflict, as a "non-end
chess game." In the "game playing," the two sides were getting
more and more experienced to smartly break the rules.
</P>
<P>
"But the point is that the Kings are not on the board," the
diplomat said, "and neither of the contestants has found it
possible to check the other one."
</P>
<P>
Trained and financed by Iran, the Lebanese Hezbollah, or Party
of God, is the main force fighting against the Israeli occupation
in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Under an understanding brokered by the United States, a
committee grouping the U.S., France, Syria, Lebanon and Israel
was established in order to monitor the cease-fire on the
 Lebanese-Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
The so-called "April cease-fire understanding" put an end to
a 17-day Israeli blitz in south Lebanon, in which some 200
Lebanese, mainly civilians, were killed.
</P>
<P>
However, the understanding gives a green light to guerrilla
attacks on Israeli forces occupying a border strip in south
Lebanon, allows the Israelis a "right of self-defense" and
demands that civilians be kept away from military operations.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and the Jewish state have raced one another to file
complaints to the five-nation committee when non-military targets
were attacked.
</P>
<P>
Until now, the committee has held seven meetings, issued four
statements, but failed to make any condemnation in spite of the
fact that over two dozens of south Lebanese villagers have been
wounded in Israel's artillery shellings since the committee was
set up in August.
</P>
<P>
Israel argued that the shellings were retaliative for the
attacks launched "from civilian areas" by guerrillas of the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, which violated the cease-fire
understanding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: A Non-End Chess Game in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A total of 25 Israeli soldiers have been killed by Hezbollah
guerrillas in south Lebanon since the beginning of this year,
including 18 killed after Israel's "Operation Grapes of Wrath" in
April.
</P>
<P>
In its last meeting in the south Lebanese border town of
Naqoura last week, the cease-fire monitoring committee confirmed
that "at least one Katyusha rocket" was fired into northern
Israel on December 13, but it declined to hold Lebanon responsible
for the offensive.
</P>
<P>
Threats posed by the Katyusha on the Jewish settlements in
northern Israel had been one of the main causes prompting former
Prime Minister Shimon Peres to launch the large-scale military
strike in south Lebanon in April.
</P>
<P>
The 17-day blitz led to the killing of some 200 Lebanese,
mostly civilians, and caused material losses estimated at 500
million to 700 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the operation did not save the Labor government from
stepping down. Shimon Peres, the former Israeli Prime Minister
suffered a defeat in the May 29 general elections and Binyamin
Netanyahu, the Likud party leader, won the race and later put
forward the "Lebanon first" proposal in an apparent attempt to
break the dilemma.
</P>
<P>
But the proposal was dismissed by Lebanon and Syria, both of
which terms it as a scheme to estrange the two close neighbors.
</P>
<P>
According to the proposal, Israel will pull its forces out of
the occupied border enclave after a security arrangement
satisfying the Jewish state is reached with Lebanon and
guaranteed by Syria.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese President Elias Hrawi said that the "Lebanese first"
proposal was aimed at "driving a wedge between Lebanon and
Syria," the last two Arab countries still in a state of war with
their Jewish neighbor.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that after the Israeli withdrawal, the Lebanese
army will guarantee tranquility and stability on the border and
will prevent any shot and bombardment directed at northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
To eliminate the resistance before the Israeli withdrawal "is
a political price Lebanon is not willing to pay," Hrawi said.
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1,100-square-kilometer buffer zone,
stretching from the Mediterranean coast in the west to Mount
Hermon in the east in 1985, in a bid to protect northern Israel
from cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Political observers rule out a solution for the south Lebanon
problem outside the framework of peace process between Lebanon
and Syria on the one side and Israel on the other. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Minister Calls for Redoubling Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Health Minister
Katele Kalumba here today called for redoubling investments in
the fight against the HIV/AIDS pandemic.
</P>
<P>
Kalumba made the remarks while officially launching a policy
document on AIDS in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
He said that Zambia made a political commitment on fighting
HIV/AIDS two years ago, but it was disappointed that there
was little financial support in the fight against the disease.
</P>
<P>
"It is sad and very disappointing that we cannot cope with the
catastrophe that has befallen us," Kalumba noted.
</P>
<P>
He added that less money is being spent on AIDS projects and
it is difficult to mobilize resources to combat the deadly
disease.
</P>
<P>
It was reported earlier that at least 500 young women in the
country are daily getting infected with HIV virus that causes the
deadly disease AIDS. In the age group of 15-39 there are about
700,000 people infected with HIV. Out of the total population of
8.9 millions, about 70 percent are youths who are at great risk
of contracting HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The spread of HIV/AIDS seems to be on the increase in Zambia,
Deputy Minister of Youth and Child Development Mutele Chitika
said earlyer. "It is therefore a matter of utmost importance and
great urgency that the young are protected from this deadly
disease AIDS." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
