<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Finalizes Agreements on Major Gas Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran claimed here today that
it has finalized agreements on a few billion dollar projects with
European and Far Eastern countries despite U.S. embargo and
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Reza Rostami Sani, director of the international affairs
department of the National Iranian Gas Co., said that the
official announcement will be made by Oil Minister Gholamreza
Aqazadeh soon.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official told Xinhua in an exclusive interview
that some companies from European and Asian countries will take
part in the massive gas projects in South Pars gas field in the
Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Iran is the second largest gas country in the world. Its
natural gas reserve stands at 21 trillion cubic meters and can
be used for 500 years.
</P>
<P>
In the summer of 1995, Iran announced 11 major oil and gas
projects with a total foreign investment of 7 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
They include the South Pars gas field development project
with an investment of 851 million dollars, the Salman Dalan gas
field development project with an investment of 572 million
dollars, the Amak gas compression and treating project with an
investment of 250 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sani said that foreign companies will undertake the massive
gas projects in form of buy-back system since the demand for gas
in Europe is bigger than the supply. Asian countries such as
Japan and South Korea have great interest in purchasing Iranian
gas. The Iranian official said that Iran has a giant gas export
project, which will transfer natural gas from the Iranian gas
field to European countries.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he added, Iran has established an joint company of
Iran-Gas Europe in cooperation with six European countries of
Austria, Spain, Germany, France, Czech Republic and Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
Specialists have spent three years in making feasibility
studies on the massive project with two ways for gas transmission
to Europe via Turkey and the Caucasus, he said.
</P>
<P>
It will take eight to 15 years to complete the gas
transmission project first to eastern Europe and then to western
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Iran now produces 40 billion cubic meters of natural gas
annually for the local market with a 16,000-kilometer main trunk
gas pipeline across the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0266 </DOCNO>
