<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Meets With Israeli Defense Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Minister of Defense
Yitzhak Mordechai today went directly into talks with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak on the imminent deal on the overdue
Israeli troop redeployment in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
They will review the lastest developments of the peace process
in the Middle East during the meeting held upon Mordechai's
arrival in the Egyptian Red Sea resort of Hurghada. Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa attended the meeting, according to
Egypt's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his departure from Tel Aviv today, Mordechai was
quoted by Israel Radio as saying that he would affirm to Mubarak
Israel's commitment to live in peace and security with its
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
He said he will brief the Egyptian president on the latest
developments concerning the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
In a relevant development, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu met with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat today at Erez
checkpoint on the border between Israel and the Gaza strip.
</P>
<P>
The meeting aims to put the final touches on the long-delayed
agreement on redeployment of Israeli forces in the last
Israeli-controlled West Bank town of Hebron, which was due to
take place in march.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Mideast peace coordinator Dennis Ross met earlier today
with Netanyahu and later with Arafat after his Cairo visit Monday.
</P>
<P>
Moussa presented a report to Mubarak on progress in the Hebron
talks after his meeting with Ross, who had been shuttling between
Palestine and Israel over the past two months.
</P>
<P>
Monday evening Mubarak received a phone call from Netanyahu.
They discussed the possibility of reaching an Israeli-Palestinian
agreement on implementing the previously concluded accords.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu clarified that some progress has been realized in
the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks on the long overdue Israeli
redeployment in the West Bank town of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic breakthrough in the talks between the Israelis
and Palestinians came Monday afternoon when Netanyahu joined the
negotiations at a hotel in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Both Arafat and Ross expressed cautious optimism following
the talks, but Ross admitted that difference remained between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the reason for the breakthrough is
a package deal Ross has been working on, which includes Israel's
commitment to further redeployment elsewhere in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Israel also would agree to hold final status
talks on the West Bank and other issues a few weeks after the
conclusion of the Hebron redeployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961224.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donation for The Elderly in Zhejiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Nineteen enterprises in east
China's Zhejiang Province today donated 3.96 million yuan (about
477,000 US dollars) for the province's five million elderly people.
</P>
<P>
The province's elderly population has seen a steady rise in
recent years. There are now 5.15 million people above the age of
60, accounting for 11.78 percent of the total population in
Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has launched a happy-life project for
the elderly, which includes building recreational centers,
schools, apartments, and hospitals for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
At present, the province has more than 15,000 elderly
organizations, 13,554 recreational centers for older people, and
over 1,500 hospitals, apartments, and old folk's homes which take
care of 21,000 aged people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
