<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Build Second Air Traffic Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 24 (Xinhua) -- A second advanced air traffic
control center will be built at Prestwick, southern London,
according to Britain's Civil Aviation Authority (CAA).
</P>
<P>
The Prestwick center, with a total investment of 200 million
pounds (325 million U.S. dollars), will be built, equipped and
owned by private sector companies, but staffed by CAA employees.
</P>
<P>
It will complement a publicly-funded center at Swanwick due to
open at the end of next year, CAA said.
</P>
<P>
The Swanwick center, also in London, was scheduled to open this
month, taking over air traffic control from facilities at West
Drayton near Heathrow airport. But the opening was put back
because of computer software problems. Swanwick's air traffic
operations room is said to be the biggest in the world.
</P>
<P>
The National Air Traffic Services, a subsidiary of the CAA,
expected the traffic it would have to handle to increase by 30
percent over the next 10 years and by up to 50 percent by 2015.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
