<HEADLINE> Britain's Post Office Profit Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Post Office's pre-tax
profit and turnover increased in the first half of the current
financial year.
</P>
<P>
Pre-tax trading profit for the first six months was 230 million
pounds (368 million U.S dollars), up from the l70 million pounds
(272 million dollars) in the same period last year, according to
half-year results released here today.
</P>
<P>
Turnover increased slightly to 3 billion pounds (4.8 billion
U.S dollars) over the same period. The increases include the
impact of the rise in postal prices which took effect in July,
when basic stamp prices rose by l penny (l.6 U.S cents).
</P>
<P>
The Post Office said in a statement that almost all the profit
would be used to pay corporation tax and satisfy the Treasury's
l996-97 cash requirement of almost 300 million pounds (480 million
U.S dollars).
</P>
<P>
"The Post Office and all its businesses will have to work hard
for the rest of the financial year if we are to meet the
government's demanding cash and efficiency targets," it said.
</P>
<P>
The Post Office also said, a record number of Christmas cards
and letters have been delivered this year, reaching the 2 billion
mark for the first time. Last year, also a record, saw l.8
billion card deliveries.
</P>
<P>
Mail volumes peaked on December l6 when more than l28 million
items were mailed -- the largest number mailed in a single day in
the Post Office's 350-year history, the Office said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
